{ About me:  I am Viktor Neustroev, a 36 year-old FIDE Master from Novosibirsk, Russia. I started playing chess early - at the age of 5, and won a lot of local trophies. Then I had a break after completing my Master's degree in Economics, and got back to it only after several years. I achieved FIDE Master level @@StartBracket@@2305@@EndBracket@@ during the tournament in Montenegro in 2019.   My daughter, Alice is also a chess player, and I coached her when she became the champion of Siberia among girls under 9 years old in 2017. I have a lot of students from different countries and most of them progress rapidly, especially two girls and a boy from the UK, who are top players of their age group in the UK.   About the course:   Why do people play the London with White? First of all, there is not much theory White should be aware of. Their typical plans are clear and straightforward. There is not much advantage for White in London System, but their position is quite solid. Some precise play is required from Black. Otherwise, White gets a small, but a stable advantage.  Why have I decided to record a course devoted to this variation?  The London System became very popular during the last 20 years. The 1. d4 & 2. Bf4 plan at first was a strong weapon against those who prefer to reply with 1...d5. That’s why many 1...d5 lovers switched to different openings such as the King’s Indian or Nimzo-Indian Defense starting with 1. d4 Nf6 or sometimes even 1. d4 e6, for example, as I did when I was much younger when the French Defense was my primary opening for Black.   I was ok to play French after the line transposes from 1. d4 e6 to a basic French position after 2. e4 d5. But what to do for those who don’t play French and instead of 1...Nf6 prefers playing such competitive lines as the Slav Defense, Semi-Slav Defense, any line of Queen’s Gambit Declined including the Cambridge Springs, Tartakower system? The last one was popular at the time of Fischer and Karpov. Such players @@StartBracket@@who prefer 1. d4 d5 positions@@EndBracket@@ should keep playing 1...d5, and learn how to react to this or that deviation from White.  That’s why I decided to create a course to explain how to handle the London System after 1. d4 d5. And in this course, there are no lines where White gets any advantage: the position is either equal or favors Black. And according to my analysis, there is nowhere White can improve.  Several strong chess players including Magnus Carlsen, Wesley So, Hikaru Nakamura, Levon Aronian, Alexander Grischuk and others play the London System from time to time and some GMs use London as their primary repertoire. You can meet it every other game with the black pieces if you play against club players. That’s why this course is definitely what you need to beat such players. I played against the London System many times and defeated many titled players. The most notable games are the one I played against IM Vladan Rabrenovic and my blitz match against FM Nikolay Yordanov. These chess players are experts in the London and understand the positions pretty well.  There are almost no books or detailed explanations of how to play against London with 1...d5, but I’ve already had some analysis prepared because played it myself. However, some lines were not covered by me and I had to study them first myself.   I based my analysis on the recommendations of strong GMs and London System experts and was following games of No.4 German, GM Matthias Bluebaum, a world-renowned expert of the London System for Black. However, every move and every idea was double-checked with the engine. That’s why I’m absolutely sure you won’t find any mistakes in the course. In many lines, it offers better positions for Black with good winning chances. My personal score with the black pieces in the London system only proves it: 60% winning, 25% drawing and only 15% losing.  However, just the knowledge of the variation is not enough to beat a strong chess player. You have to be good in the other chess aspects. But opening knowledge offers some advantage, of course.   Before diving into the theory, please familiarize yourself withthe basic setup.   Viktor Neustroev }
1. -- *

