[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "The Basic Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is what Queen’s Gambit, Catalan and London System players typically start with. Black answers with }
1... d5
{ which offers a lot of options to continue including such solid defenses as the Slav and Semi-Slav. The Slav is ok, if you are alright with drawing the game, but you can play for a win in the Semi-Slav. The second move could be }
2. Bf4
{ Or  2.Nf3  is more flexible and allows White to transpose to a Queen’s Gambit, for example. That’s why we also keep our pawn structure flexible and first play  2...Nf6  inviting White to transpose from London to another Queen’s Pawn line. }
2... c5
{ The second move for Black is either 2...c5 or 2...Nf6. The logic here is simple: if White doesn’t fight for the center with their c-pawn, Black will. That’s why, with 2...c5, Black wants to undermine White’s center and to overtake the initiative. 2...c5 also allows Black to develop their queen to b6. While the white bishop is already on f4, the b2-pawn becomes weak.  Including such moves as Nf3 and ...Nf6 doesn’t change the position much, but restricts White’s options in case they decide to play the London.   In this position, White has several options starting with rare moves such as 3. dxc5, 3. e4, and 3. Nc3. }
3. e3 { Black continues with } 3... Nf6
{ In practice, there is no difference which knight develops first. I just suggest 3...Nf6 to make the lines easier to remember. In this position, the mainline is }
4. Nf3
{ Developing a knight and putting pressure on the d4-pawn. After this move, Black intends to move their queen to b6 and double attack the d- and b-pawns. White continues with }
4... Nc6 5. c3
{ Supporting the center and probably preparing to move the queen to the queenside. }
5... Qb6
{ Attacking a weakness on b2. The most common options for White here are 3 queen moves: 6. Qb3, 6. Qc2 & 6. Qc1. All these options are covered in all details in my course: }
6. Qb3
{ 6.b3  is possible, but creates more weakness in White’s camp.  6...Bg4   6.Qc1  cxd4   6.Qc2  g6 }
6... c4
{ Conclusion:  In the course, I give a full overview of options against each move and explain my choices, and sometimes I offer more than one solution, so you can choose depending on your playing style.  I structured the course and divided it into 12 chapters with Variations and 1 Chapter with 12 Model games; One model game per chapter. The games are well explained and illustrate typical plans Black applies in London System. As for the Variations, in the first 5 chapters, I mainly demonstrate some rare variations that may happen in the games between club players and are quite rare in GMs’ games especially with standard time control. The most popular variations among grandmasters are shown in chapters6,7,8,9,11 &12.  Nowadays, chess players @@StartBracket@@especially top GMs@@EndBracket@@ understand that it’s almost impossible to get any opening advantage with White if Black plays a competitive opening properly. That’s why, a chess player who is more familiar with the arising positions and understands the typical ideas better has an edge. This is the reason why people still play the London with White. They just are so familiar with these positions and know exactly which plans to apply.  Don’t miss your chance to learn how to respond and outplay your opponent in London System with the black pieces. I am sure this will be useful for players of absolutely all levels, especially if you play 1...d5 against 1. d4. However, if you respond with 1...Nf6, maybe you’ll change your mind and will start playing 1...d5 because of Black's huge prospects in these lines against the London System  . }
