1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ All typical 3rd moves are explained in other chapters. Here I wanted to demonstrate what may happen in case if white chooses rare moves. Sometimes it transposes to the positions we already know, but sometimes leads to sharp variation, where Black, of course, obtains some advantage. }
3. c4
{ This resembles an Austrian Defense with the unnecessary and rather useless move, Bf4. }
3... cxd4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Please remember that in weird positions, development is your main priority. }
5. Nxd4 Nbd7 { Threatening a fork. } 6. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Black centralizes the knight and creates direct threats. } 7. Bg3 e5
{ 8.Nf3  or 8. Nb3 fails to  8...Bb4+  after which White has to defend the position and only and hope that Black eases the pressure. }
8. Nc2 Qa5+
{ Not the only option, but the most active one. If you want to continue playing positionally, just retreat with your knight  8...N5f6  with equality. }
9. Nd2 h5
{ Black has no problems with their development, while White has to stay under pressure. }
