1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ All typical 3rd moves are explained in other chapters. Here I wanted to demonstrate what may happen in case if white chooses rare moves. Sometimes it transposes to the positions we already know, but sometimes leads to sharp variation, where Black, of course, obtains some advantage. }
3. Bxb8 { A strategic mistake, but White has some concrete ideas in mind. }
3... Rxb8 4. c3 Nf6
{ 4...cxd4  is a good alternative with the idea to play 5...Qb6. } 5. dxc5 Qc7
6. b4 { Trying to save the pawn. } 6... b6
{ This is how Black weakens the white pawns on the queenside to make them the objects of attack. }
7. cxb6 Rxb6
{ Black is a pawn down, but with the bishop pair, center control and better development, they have more chances to succeed in this game. }
