1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ All typical 3rd moves are explained in other chapters. Here I wanted to demonstrate what may happen in case if white chooses rare moves. Sometimes it transposes to the positions we already know, but sometimes leads to sharp variation, where Black, of course, obtains some advantage. }
3. Nf3 { This move may or may not to transpose to one of the main lines. } 3...
cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 { Gaining a tempo. } 5. Qd3 a6
{ To prevent Nb5, Qb5 or Bb5 in future. } 6. Nbd2 f6
{ This is how Black takes control over the center. A typical idea when the d4-pawn is removed. }
7. e4 { An attempt to get counterplay. } 7... e5 8. Bg3 Be6
{ White's bishop on g3 is locked out. Black takes it into the endgame favoring them. If White doesn't take on d5, Black may continue with d4, obtain some space and threaten ...Nb4-c2. }
