[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4
{ This is the 3rd most popular move in this position. However, some strong Grandmasters recommend it and play this line mainly in blitz. If we just reverse colors, it will be similar to Albin Counter-Gambit, but with the bishop on f4, which sometimes is useless, sometimes not. }
3... dxe4
{ The main move for this position. To refute a gambit, you should accept it! However, such moves like 3...Nc6 and 3...Nf6 are also playable. For example, Magnus Carlsen played them in some of his online blitz games. }
4. d5
{ This move reflects the main idea of this variation. White grabs some space in the center and slows down Black's development. }
4... Nf6
{ A natural developing move that forces White to defend the central pawn. } 5.
c4
{ This move is quite uncommon. However, this is what you can meet in the games between club players. White protects the central pawn but restricts their light-squared bishop. }
5... e6 { Undermining the center. } 6. Nc3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Nge2
{ Planning to gain the e4-pawn back. } 8... O-O 9. Ng3 Qe5
{ The black queen cannot be attacked in the center and offers protection for the e-pawn. Black continues with Rd8 and Na6 and just captures the pawn on d5. }
