1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4
{ This is the 3rd most popular move in this position. However, some strong Grandmasters recommend it and play this line mainly in blitz. If we just reverse colors, it will be similar to Albin Counter-Gambit, but with the bishop on f4, which sometimes is useless, sometimes not. }
3... dxe4
{ The main move for this position. To refute a gambit, you should accept it! However, such moves like 3...Nc6 and 3...Nf6 are also playable. For example, Magnus Carlsen played them in some of his online blitz games. }
4. d5
{ This move reflects the main idea of this variation. White grabs some space in the center and slows down Black's development. }
4... Nf6
{ A natural developing move that forces White to defend the central pawn. } 5.
Nc3 g6
{ There is no need to fight for the e4 pawn. We can sacrifice it back in order to finish development. }
6. Nb5 { This is how GM Andrew Tang likes to play. } 6... Na6 7. d6 Be6
{ Taking on d6 means to exchange a dark-squared bishop for knight. White may offer it anyway after 8. dxe7 @@StartBracket@@Black may accept or not@@EndBracket@@, but we'd better spend a tempo on something useful. For example, on our light-squared bishop development. }
8. dxe7 Bxe7 9. Nd6+ Kf8
{ 9...Bxd6  is a possible move as well; we'd better keep the dark-squared bishop alive. Moreover, there is nothing White can do to progress.   For example, @@StartFEN@@r2q1k1r/pp2bp1p/n2Nbnp1/2p5/4pB2/8/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bh6+  Kg8  and the d6-knight is hanging while Black is a pawn up. }
10. Nxb7 Qb6 11. Nd6 Rd8 { White faces material losses. } *

