[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Impatient 3.dxc5: 4.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up the center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. e4 Bxc5
{ Taking the e4-pawn and passing the game into the endgame favors White. The black king would move, and the e4-pawn would be a weakness. }
5. Nc3 Qb6 6. Qd2 Nf6
{ 6...Qxb2  is a blunder due to  7.Rb1  Qa3  8.Rb3  Qa5  9.Rb5  Qa3  10.Nb1  Qxa2  11.Qc3  with several simultaneous threats: trap the queen with Ra5, capture the bishop and the g7-pawn!   6...Bxf2+  is too early because of  7.Qxf2  Qxb2  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Nge2  Qxa1+  10.Bc1  Bxb5  11.O-O  There is no knight on f6, that's why castling is a tempo move and white is threatening with Qxf7 what may lead to huge material losses for Black. However, after  11...Nf6  in this position white continues with  12.Ba3  and gains the queen. }
7. O-O-O Bb4
{ This is how Black protects the d5-pawn indirectly! In case of   7...Bxf2  White gains the pawn on d5 and opens the position. }
8. Qd3
{ The only move that allows White to keep this position equal. Black has two possible options here which lead to the same position. }
8... Bxc3 9. Qxc3 { The bishop on c8 is hanging. } 9... O-O
{ White's f2 and e4-pawns are hanging. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black exchanges their knight for the bishop. } 11. Qg3 Nxf4 12. Qxf4 Nc6
{ White has a choice now: to let Black play ...e6-e5 and develop the light-squared bishop or continue with 13. Nf3 and sacrifice the f2-pawn. In both cases, the position will be approximately equal. }
