1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up the center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Bd3
{ A typical move for the London System. White believes this bishop controls the e4-square and potentially can join a kingside attack. }
6... Nc6
{ This is where White has several options. However, some of them are just transpositions. }
7. Nbd2
{ A more flexible move for White which allows them to play c2-c4 in future. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Re8
{ Instead of ...Qe7, Black plays ...Re8 with the same idea - to push the e-pawn. }
9. Ne5 { Blocking the e-pawn. } 9... Bd6 10. Nxc6
{ 10.Ndf3  doesn't make much sense, just  10...Qc7  and White has to take anyway. }
10... bxc6
{ Black takes control over the e5-square and gets a semi-open b-file for their rook. }
11. Bxd6 { Undermining the center. } 11... Qxd6 12. c4 e5
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...e4, ...d4, ...h6, ...Bd7@@StartBracket@@or ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@ & ...Rab8. }
