1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up the center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black has to castle on the kingside anyway, so this is the best move for them. }
7. a3 Nc6 { The best place for the knight on b8 is the c6 square. } 8. b4 Bd6
{ With the idea of ...e5. } 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. c4 a5
{ A typical move for Black - the idea is to make these pawns weaker. } 11. cxd5
exd5 12. b5 Ne5
{ Black has an isolated pawn. Their plan is to play: ...Bg4, ...Rfc8, ...Rc3, ...h6 and to attack the pawns on the queenside. }
