1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. }
3... Nc6 4. e4 { An attempt to impose sharp complications. } 4... cxd4 5. Nb5
{ Leads to a forced variation... } 5... e5 { To prevent the Nc7+ fork. } 6.
exd5 { 6...Qxd5  falls under the  7.Nc7+  fork. } 6... exf4 7. dxc6 Bb4+ 8. c3
Qe7+ 9. Qe2 { White is threatening a Nc7+ fork. } 9... dxc3
{ To create a counter-threat. } 10. bxc3 bxc6 11. cxb4 cxb5 12. Qxe7+
{ to gain the pawn on f4 after Ne2. Otherwise, White is a pawn down. } 12...
Kxe7 13. Ne2 Nf6 14. Nxf4 Rd8
{ Black is slightly better in this endgame due to their pieces activity and better development. The b5-pawn is a poisoned pawn. After  15.Bxb5  ,  Black grabs the pawn back with  15...Rb8  . }
