[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 { A logical developing move to support the center. } 4... Nf6
5. e3 Bg4
{ With the idea to exchange Black's potentially bad light-squared bishop. } 6.
Be2 e6 7. O-O Bxf3 8. Bxf3 cxd4
{ This move clearly illustrates that the knight on c3 is almost useless. In these type of positions, this knight should support the e5-square. }
9. exd4 Bd6 10. Be3
{ White doesn't want to lose a bishop pair and decides to avoid this exchange. }
10... O-O 11. Ne2 b5
{ Now Black can successfully occupy the c4-square to pressure the b2-pawn and maybe to exchange that knight for a bishop @@StartBracket@@it depends on the concrete position@@EndBracket@@. Playing b2-b3 creates a weakness on c3, but White can't tolerate the knight on c4! }
*

