[Black "Jobava Attack: 4.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. }
3... Nc6 4. e3
{ In this variation, Black is able at least to equalize the position and get comfortable play. }
4... cxd4 { The most competitive move. } 5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bb5
{ Ambitious, but practically leads to all positions favoring Black. } 6... e6
{ In this position, the best set up for Black is: ...Nge7, ...Ng6, ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Rac8 & ...a6. }
7. Nf3 Bd6
{ But not  7...Bb4  after which White can just castle. The black dark-squared bishop should be developed first, allowing the g8-knight to move to e7. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Ne7
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...O-O, ...a6, ...b5, ...Qb6, ...h6. } *

