[Black "The Solid 3.c3: 4.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. c3
{ This is actually the second most popular move. However, almost always this line is transposed to other London System variations with pawns on e3 and c3. }
3... Nc6 { To control e5 and threaten ...Qd8-b6. } 4. dxc5
{ A logical move when the pawn is on c3, but in this exact position, the bishop on f4 becomes the object of attack! }
4... e5 5. Bg3
{ 5.Be3  d4!  and White gets an almost losing position where they have to only defend! }
5... h5
{ Black has a strong center and the bishop on g3 is isolated from the game. }
6. h3 Nf6
{ 6...Bxc5  looks good as well, but then White may play  7.b4  with a tempo and then even 8. b5 chasing our knight away from the defense of e5. }
7. b4 Ne4
{ We centralize our knight and want to take the bishop on g3 and to destroy the pawns structure. }
8. Bh2 a5
{ A typical idea for Black when the opponent has this kind of pawns structure on the queenside. }
9. b5 Bxc5 { Threatening mate. } 10. e3 Qh4 11. g3
{ In case of  11.Qe2  ,  just  11...Nb4  threatening a fork on c2. } 11... Qf6
12. Nf3 Ne7
{ and Black protects everything. With equal material on the board, they dominate the center and with great piece activity. }
*

