1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. c3
{ This is actually the second most popular move. However, almost always this line is transposed to other London System variations with pawns on e3 and c3. }
3... Nc6 { To control e5 and threaten ...Qd8-b6. } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2
{ A typical move, but a mistake in this exact position. } 5... cxd4
{ the early ...cxd4 most of the time is always good because Black doesn't let White play dxc5 & b4 and to create a counter-attack on the queenside. }
6. cxd4
{ In such positions, the queenside knight should be located on c3 - it has almost nothing to do on d2. That's why 5. Nbd2 was a mistake. }
6... Nh5
{ one of the typical ideas in the London system for black is to attack the bishop on f4 }
7. Bg3 Nxg3 { This bishop is better than a knight. } 8. hxg3 Qb6
{ One of the best spots for the queen and a double attack, of course. } 9. e3
e6
{ 9...Qxb2  offers some initiative for White after  10.Rb1  Qxa2  11.Bb5  . That's why it's better just to continue development. }
10. Rb1 Bd7
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Be7, ...O-O, ...g6, ...a5 & ...e5!? With a bishop pair their task is to open the position. }
