[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. exd4 Bf5
{ A typical Carlsbad pawn structure with reversed colors. Here it's better to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain. }
8. Be2 Rc8
{ Right now the d4-pawn is not hanging but after this move, Black keeps in mind the idea of playing ...Nc6-b4-d3 }
9. O-O h6
{ Securing the bishop on f5. After that we have to finish our development: ...e6, ...Be7 & ...O-O  . }
10. Nbd2 e6
{ 10...g5 is a good alternative, but deserves detailed analysis. For example,  10...g5  11.Be5  Bg7  and the position is unclear. }
11. h3 Be7 12. Bd1 Rg8
{ Offers a strong attack on the kingside while the enemy queen is located on the queenside and cannot support the king's position. }
