[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc2 g6
{ Please notice  6...Bf5  doesn't work. White should avoid  7.Qxf5  when Black, of course, captures the pawn and gains the rook after  7...Qxb2  & 8...Qxa1.   But instead of taking on f5 immediately, White should first play @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp2pppp/1qn2n2/2pp1b2/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PPQ2PPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.dxc5  attacking the black queen. If  7...Qxc5  the bishop on f5 is hanging while the black queen no longer attacks b2. That's why Black has to capture the queen with  7...Bxc2  8.cxb6  axb6  and White is better, the position is open, and they can successfully activate their light-squared bishop. 6...g6 makes more sense. Black wants to fianchetto, and also keeps in mind to play ...Bc8-f5 later in the game. }
7. dxc5 { After this move, Black has the chance to control the center. } 7...
Qxc5 8. Nbd2
{ The most natural way to develop the knight. Later it goes to b3 and d4. }
8... Bg7 9. Nb3 Qb6 { The only square for the queen. } 10. Bd3 O-O
{ Black just continues their development according to the plan. } 11. O-O Nh5
{ Exchanging the knight for a bishop. } 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3
{ Now Black has a pair of bishops and controls the center with their pawns. }
13... Rd8 { Another option is to play  13...Bg4  . } 14. a4
{ Intending to pressure the queen and provoking 14...a5. } 14... a5 15. Nbd2 h5
{ This move is required to protect the bishop on g4. For example, in case White moves their knight and attacks the g4-bishop, instead of spending a tempo to retreat it, Black may play something better. For example, occupy the center with the pawn or threaten something. Black has a bishop pair and dominates in the center. They need to consolidate and come up with a plan according to what white plays. }
*

