[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qb3: 7.Qxb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qxb6 axb6
{ Doubling the pawns on the b-file only improves the black position. They get a clear plan, and an open file. The endgame is preferable for Black and they have two strong plans: The first one is to put the bishop on f5 and to play ...h6, and the second one is to play ...e6 and ...Bd7. }
8. Nbd2 b5
{ The plan is to play ...b5-b4 and to create a weakness on the queenside. } 9.
a3
{ To prevent b5-b4,  however, playing  9...b4  is still possible because of the pin on the a-file. }
9... Bf5 10. Rc1 { Getting rid of the pin on the a-file. } 10... h6
{ To reinforce the position of our light-squared bishop on f5. } 11. Be2 e6 12.
h3 Nd7
{ The b2-pawn now becomes the object of the attack. Our light-squared successfully secures the c2- and b1-squares and the b-pawn can't be protected. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qb3: 7.Qc2, 9.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qc2
{ The only other option.  7.Qa3  is a blunder due to  7...e5  attacking queen and bishop simultaneously. }
7... Bf5
{ If White takes this bishop  8.Qxf5  they lose the b2-pawn and the rook after  8...Qxb2  . }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qe2  blocks the bishop and  8.Qd2  fails to  8...Ne4  with a tempo. Black has to develop their pieces on the kingside. }
8... e6 9. h3 Be7 10. Nbd2
{ In this position there are two main options for Black: ...h6 - to protect their light-squared bishop or just ...O-O and let White exchange their knight for the black dark-squared bishop. However, a deep analysis shows that O-O gives more chances for Black to win the game, while ...h6 is safer. You can play both options. }
10... O-O
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfc8, ...Qd8, ...b5 & ...b4 and to start an attack on the queenside. }
11. Be2 Rfc8
{ Black doesn't lose a tempo with ...h6 but immediately starts the plan. } 12.
O-O Qd8 { Vacating the b-file for the pawn march. } 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4
{ White intends to exchange their knight for our light-squared bishop. This is actually one of the disadvantages of not playing ...h6 in time. However, without ...h6 Black saved a tempo and may progress on the queenside faster. A very interesting game in that position is between Mufic,G - Mikhalchishin,A 2001, 0-1. }
14... b5 15. Nxg6 hxg6
{ Black can play on the queenside with ...b4, ...a5, ...a4 and also in the center with ...Nd7 & ...e5. }
*

