[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Bd3
{ A possible, but slow move. White lost an important pawn on b2, their task is to develop the initiative as fast as they can. That's why 7. Rb1 is a more logical continuation. }
7... g6
{ Not the only possible response, but definitely the best one.  7...e6  or 7... Qc3 can be played as well. The idea of 7...g6 is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, pressure through the main diagonal and castle as soon as possible. However, this move is not well-studied and was played only once. The c5-pawn is a weakness and can be taken by the black queen. }
8. Nd4 a6
{ To secure the b5-square. The white knight on b5 also could restrict our queen activity. }
9. Rb1 Qa3
{ 9...Qc3 can be played as well, but   9...Qxa2  is a critical mistake.  10.Ra1  attacking the queen,  10...Qb2  and  11.Nb5  ,  the a6-pawn is pinned, because of the open a-file. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O
{ While there are no active moves, White finishes their development. } 11...
Bg7
{ Development is our first priority. The c5-pawn can be taken later with the queen. }
12. Be5 O-O
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Qxc5, ...Nd7, ...a5 and ...Ba6 to exchange light-squared bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 7.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for b=Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. c4
{ Another common response in this variation. White tries to open up the position and mobilize his pieces as fast as possible to be able to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
7... e6
{ Supporting the center.  7...Bf5  to prevent Ra1-b1 is a good alternative. However, in my opinion, it may be too risky to move the bishop outside the pawn chain too early. White can impose some complications with Bf1-b5 in future. }
8. Rb1 Qxa2 9. Ra1 Qb2 10. Rb1
{ In this position, White can't repeat the position and claim a draw. The black queen finds a way to escape. }
10... Qa3 11. cxd5 Nxd5 { The best place for the knights is in the center! }
12. Bb5 Be7
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...O-O, ...Qa5, ...Qc3, with a slightly better position. }
*

