[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 7.Rb1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for b=Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Rb1 Qc3
{ Not ...Qa2 - the black queen can get trapped there. And not ...Qa3 @@StartBracket@@which is actually possible@@EndBracket@@. Here on c3 the queen is more helpful. At least it pins the knight. }
8. Bb5 e6
{ 8...g6!?  also deserves attention but requires additional analysis. } 9. O-O
Be7
{ Important! Don't take the c5-pawn with your bishop. The c5-square is reserved for your queen. }
10. Nb3
{ This is how White intends to create a net to trap the queen, but usually, it doesn't work and the black queen can escape. }
10... O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nfd4 Bxc5 13. Nxc6 Bb6
{ Not  13...Bxe3  ,  because of intermediate check  14.Ne7  . This is an ideal square for our dark-squared bishop. It still controls the center and blocks the b-file. Here Black's plan is to pressure on the c-file and control the position in the center. }
