[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3
{ This is a different move order which allows White to save a tempo on a knight move but develop the bishop to prevent Black from playing ...Bf5. However, this move has its own disadvantages which i will illustrate. }
5... Qb6 { Same idea - to attack the b-pawn. } 6. Qc1
{ The most popular move. } 6... cxd4 7. exd4 e5
{ There is no knight on f3 and Black takes the advantage of it immediately. }
8. dxe5 Ng4 { Black increases their initiative and gains the pawn back. } 9.
Bg3 Bc5 { developing the bishop with a tempo. } 10. Qc2
{ Supporting the f2-pawn. } 10... Ngxe5 11. b4 Bd4
{ Intending to capture on b4. } 12. Bxe5 Bxe5
{ Black is much better here with a bishop pair and better piece activity. } *

