[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 e6
{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. Qb3 Qc8
{ With this move we keep the position more complicated.  7...Qd7  fails to  8.Ne5  with Bf1-b5 ideas. }
8. Bb5 c4
{ An important move where we take the space advantage on the queenside and put pressure on White's pieces. }
9. Qd1 Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ Next we can just play ...h6 to let our bishop escape if required. Or just play on the queenside, initiating a pawn march! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
