{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. h3 Qb6 8. Nh4 Be4
{ Of course, we stick to our plan - when the knight goes to h4, we move the bishop on e4 and provoke f3. }
9. f3 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qb3 c4
{ A typical move for Black, trying to have more space on the queenside. } 12.
Qc2 e5
{ Black is developed better and opening the position favors them. Taking on e5 twice leads to a ...Qxe3+ fork in the end of this line. After that, Black takes the advantage of the dark-square weaknesses on the kingside in the white camp. }
