[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves: 2.Nf3, 3.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3
{ This position is likely to transpose to the London System, however, White may even play something different. }
3... c5 4. dxc5
{ 4.Bf4  Nc6  transposes to the lines covered in this chapter. } 4... e6
{ Threatening to take the pawn on c5 immediately. } 5. b4
{ 5.Be3  Works only in case White decides to fianchetto on the kingside. Otherwise, the white light-squared bishop is blocked.  5...Be7  6.g3  O-O  Black continues their development keeping. There will be a chance to capture the pawn later in the game.  7.Bg2  a5  Prevents White from playing b4. The c5-pawn is a weakness now and Black gets a clear plan how to take it with their knight.  8.O-O  Na6  9.c4  White tries to undermine the center, this is their only chance to fight for counterplay. Otherwise, Black captures the pawn and controls the center.  9...Bxc5  10.Bxc5  Nxc5  Black may avoid an isolated pawn if they take on d5 with their knight. White has some pressure on the main diagonal with their bishop, however, Black plays ...b6 and fianchettos their light-squared bishop. }
5... a5
{ To undermine the white queenside pawn structure and win the pawn back. } 6.
e3
{ While Black tries to gain the pawn back, White continues their development and keeps in mind Bb5+ ideas.   I.  6.Qb3  b6  Black exchanges the c5-pawn to be able to activate the queen and attack the b4 pawn.  7.cxb6  Qxb6  8.Be3   8.b5  is met by  8...a4  After which white queen has to stay on b2 and black locate their pieces to almost ideal positions.  Qc7  9.Bd2  g6  Similar as Catalan for White. Here Black pressures through the a1-h8 diagonal and b- and c-files.   II.  6.Bb2  b6  Attacking the pawn on c5. If White captures on b6, they weaken the b4-pawn.  7.a4  With the idea to play b5 and create a protected passed pawn.   7.e3  Continues piece development and lets Black capture the pawn back.  7...axb4  8.cxb4  bxc5  With equal material, Black finally got a better pawn structure. Their task is to exchange light-squared bishops and occupy open files on the queenside.  7...bxc5  8.b5  c4  White got a protected passed, however, it's their only benefit. Both white bishops are bad and Black controls the center. }
6... axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ A typical idea to undermine the queenside and gain the pawn back. } 8. Bb5+
{ Otherwise Black gains the pawn on c5 immediately and gets a better pawn structure. }
8... Bd7 { 8...Nbd7  9.c6  wins for White. } 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Black gains the pawn anyway and has more prospects in the middlegame with the better pawn structure in the center. Moreover, they already exchanged their bad light-squared bishop. }
*

