1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ All typical 3rd moves are explained in other chapters. Here I wanted to demonstrate what may happen in case if white chooses rare moves. Sometimes it transposes to the positions we already know, but sometimes leads to sharp variation, where Black, of course, obtains some advantage. }
3. c4
{ This resembles an Austrian Defense with the unnecessary and rather useless move, Bf4. }
3... cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Bxb8
{ From a strategic point of view, this move is bad because White exchanges their active bishop for Black's inactive knight. }
5... Rxb8 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. e4 Nb6
{ The knight on f6 would block Black's dark-squared bishop. } 8. Bb5+
{ In case of  8.Qxd8+  Black gets a better endgame, because of the bishop pair. }
8... Bd7 9. a4 Bxb5
{ Black has several other alternatives such as  9...Rc8  or  9...e6  ,  but exchanging bishops and queens provides Black with a better position. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { The rook has to stay on b8 to protect the pawn on b7. } 11.
axb5 g6
{ Even without a pawn the endgame favors Black because of their piece activity. }
12. Rxa7 Bg7 13. Nc3
{ This is how White saves the b2-pawn, but now Black has 2 plans: to regain the pawn immediately after 13...Nc4 or @@StartBracket@@a better one@@EndBracket@@ continue with 13...Kc7 to play 14...Ra8 and enter the enemy camp with the other rook. }
13... Kc7
{ Black now continues with 14...Ra8 and enters the enemy camp with the other rook. }
