3. Nf3 { This move may or may not to transpose to one of the main lines. } 3...
cxd4 4. c3 dxc3 5. Nxc3 e6 6. e4
{ The only chance for White to take the intiative. } 6... dxe4 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The endgame is equal but Black has to play properly because of White's piece activity. }
8. O-O-O+ Ke8
{ The safest spot for the king at the moment when the king also protects the f7-pawn. }
9. Ne5 { Attacking the d7-square in advance. } 9... Nf6 10. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Black defended very well and now there are two main forced options for White where Black has to play accurately. }
11. Nxe4
{ To distract the f6-knight @@StartBracket@@a defender of d7@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Nxe4 12. Nxd7 a6 { First, Black has to get rid of that pin. } 13. Nb6+
{ A better option. } 13... axb5 { This line leads to a draw by force. } 14.
Nxa8 Nxf2 { Black gains the exchange back. } 15. Nc7+ Ke7 16. Bd6+
{ provoking Black to play with their king to f6 and fall into a Rhf1 pin. }
16... Kd8 17. Bxf8+ { A discovered check. } 17... Nxd1 18. Rxd1+ Kxc7
{ And now the position is simplified! } 19. Bxg7 Rg8 20. Be5+
{ Unfortunately, Black doesn't take the g2-pawn. } 20... Kc6
{ We have an equal endgame with one extra pawn for Black. Only Black can win, but, of course, 90% of all games in this position will end in a draw. However, to reach this position, your opponent has to learn 20 moves which are almost impossible, at least at club level. }
