{ A natural developing move that forces White to defend the central pawn. } 5.
c4
{ This move is quite uncommon. However, this is what you can meet in the games between club players. White protects the central pawn, but restricts their light-squared bishop. }
5... e6 { Undermining the center. } 6. Qa4+
{ To provoke Bd7 and weaken the b7-pawn. } 6... Bd7 7. Qb3 b5
{ One of the ways to prove that a gambit is incorrect is to sacrifice the pawn back, but improve the overall position. }
8. dxe6 Bxe6 9. Qxb5+
{ White gains a pawn back, but played a lot of moves with their queen, which means tempo losses. }
9... Bd7 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. Ne2 Be7
{ The material is equal, but Black almost finished their development, while white hasn't. Moreover, Black is about to occupy the d4-square with their knight, exchange knights and get the c-pawn to d4. a5 and a4 can be played as well to pressure the enemy queen. }
