[White "2. The Aggressive 3.e4"]
[Black "The Aggressive 3.e4: 5.Nc3, 6.Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4
{ This is the 3rd most popular move in this position. However, some strong Grandmasters recommend it and play this line mainly in blitz. If we just reverse colors, it will be similar to Albin Counter-Gambit, but with the bishop on f4, which sometimes is useless, sometimes not. }
3... dxe4
{ The main move for this position. To refute a gambit you should accept it! However, such moves as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3PPB2/8/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3PPB2/8/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  are also playable. For example, Magnus Carlsen played them in some of his online blitz games. }
4. d5
{ This move reflects the main idea of this variation. White grabs some space in the center and slows down Black's development. }
4... Nf6
{ A natural developing move that forces White to defend the central pawn. } 5.
Nc3 g6
{ There is no need to fight for the e4 pawn. We can sacrifice it back in order to finish development. }
6. Nge2 Bg7 7. Qd2
{ With the idea to castle queenside and attack on the kingside later in the game. }
7... O-O 8. Ng3 e6 9. d6 Qb6 10. Bc4 Qb4
{ Attacking the bishop.  10...Qxb2  is still possible, but offers some counterplay for White after  11.Rb1  11...Qa3  . }
11. Bb3 b5
{ A multifunctional move: gaining space, threatening to trap the bishop and with the idea to fianchetto the black light-squared bishop and protect the e4-pawn. }
12. a3 Qa5
{ White can't capture the e4-pawn, because the b2-pawn is hanging when the main diagonal opens. }
13. h4
{ It's difficult to suggest a good move for White, however, h4 might be useful. In case White solves their problem in the center and on the queenside, they could consider a kingside attack. }
13... c4 14. Ba2 Bb7
{ Now Black has two good bishops. In case White plays slowly, Black finishes their development after ...Nbd7. But if White plays aggressively for example, h5, Black may push the e-pawn forward and play ...Nd5 to exchange the queens and open the diagonals for their bishops. Without queens on the board, White won't succeed with their kingside attack. }
