[White "3. The Impatient 3.dxc5"]
[Black "The Impatient 3.dxc5: 4.Nf3, 6.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Be2
{ The most popular move in this position. } 6... Qb6
{ Not a novelty actually. This move was played once in GMs' game, but after that, they immediately agreed to a draw. }
7. O-O { Provoking Black to capture the b2-pawn. } 7... Qxb2 8. Be5 Qb6 9. Bxf6
{ Thit was the original idea of a pawn sacrfice. } 9... gxf6 10. c4
{ While Black is undeveloped, White tries to open the position in the center. }
10... dxc4 { Otherwise, White captures on d5 and ruins our pawn structure. }
11. Nbd2 O-O
{ The king is safe enough there because Black can always relocate their bishop to g7 to cover it. }
12. Rc1 Nc6 13. Rxc4
{ This is how White wants to transfer their pieces to the kingside and initiate an attack. In case of  13.Nxc4  the black queen retreats and there is not full compensation for the pawn sacrifice. }
13... f5
{ Black limits White's potential ideas of the kingside attack. In case of  14.e4  Black continues with  14...Rd8  15.exf5  exf5  with bishop to e6 that cements their position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Impatient 3.dxc5"]
[Black "The Impatient 3.dxc5: 4.Nf3, 6.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Be2
{ The most popular move in this position. } 6... Qb6
{ Not a novelty actually. This move was played once in GMs' game, but after that, they immediately agreed to a draw. }
7. Qc1 Nc6 8. a3 { Planning 9.b4 with tempo and Nbd2, c4 after that. } 8... Nh5
9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 g5
{ Allows Black to grab space on the kingside and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Bf8
{ There is no alternative for the black dark-squared bishop which will add pressure through the main diagonal.  13.Nxg5  is a blunder because  13...Bg7  is a tempo move against b2 that also protects the h8-rook and leaves the g5-knight hanging. }
*

