[White "3. The Impatient 3.dxc5"]
[Black "The Impatient 3.dxc5: 4.Nf3, 6.Be2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Be2
{ The most popular move in this position. } 6... Qb6
{ Not a novelty actually. This move was played once in GMs' game, but after that, they immediately agreed to a draw. }
7. c4 Qxb2 8. Be5 d4
{ This time,  8...Qb6  is too risky as White captures on f6 and gains the d5-pawn. }
9. Nbd2 { Protecting the rook with their queen. } 9... Nc6 10. exd4 Nxe5 11.
dxe5 Nd7 { The e5-pawn is weak and white can't save it anymore! } 12. O-O O-O
13. Ne4 Be7 14. Rb1
{ Leaving the a2-pawn unprotected. The e5-pawn is more important, it creates an outpost on d6. }
14... Qa3 { 14...Qxa2  leads to a threefold repetition after Rb1-a1-b1. } 15.
Qc2 Qa5 16. Rb5 { To save the e5-pawn. } 16... Qc7
{ Now White's rooks are the object of the attack. After 17...a6 it will move back and the e5-pawn can be captured. }
17. Neg5 g6 18. Qe4
{ Protecting the pawn and moving the queen to the kingside to attack h7. }
18... Kg7 { Supporting ...h7-h6. } 19. Qh4 Bxg5
{ Right now  19...h6  fails to  20.Nxe6+  with a discovered attack. } 20. Qxg5
h6 21. Qe3 b6
{ White saved a pawn for a while. But it's still a weakness. After Black finished their development they may consider exchanging their bishop for a knight and capture it anyway. }
*

