[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Impatient 3.dxc5"]
[Black "The Impatient 3.dxc5: 4.Nf3, 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5
{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. Bd3
{ A typical move for the London System. White believes this bishop controls the e4-square and potentially can join a kingside attack. }
6... Nc6
{ This is where White has several options. However, some of them are just transpositions. }
7. c3 O-O { This is the main set up for Black which appears in many lines. } 8.
Nbd2 Qe7 { With the idea of ...e5. } 9. Bg5 h6
{ A very tricky and logical move. We can play ...g5, ...e5 and start an attack on the kingside. }
10. Bxf6 { White understands and exchanges their bishop instead. } 10... Qxf6
11. O-O Rd8
{ Black has the pair of bishops and a very solid position. Their plan is to play: ...Bb6, ...e5, ...d4 & ...Bg4. }
*

