{ A sharp continuation that surprisingly demonstrates good statistics for White in this variation. You should understand that giving up center control in the very beginning of the game may offer only an equal or worse position for White. However, some precise play is required from Black. }
3... e6
{ The most solid response. Black destroys the c5-pawn and prepares to castle kingside. }
4. Nf3 Bxc5 { 5...Qb6 is now a potential threat. } 5. e3 Nf6 6. c3
{ A typical move that makes it easier for White to protect the b2-pawn. Together with this idea, White has in mind playing b2-b4 to grab some space on the queenside. }
6... O-O 7. Nbd2 Nc6
{ Black's plan is to play ...e6-e5, not only to control the center, but to activate the light-squared bishop as well. }
8. Be2 { This line is analyzedhere from another move order. } *

