[Round "?"]
[White "4. 3.Nc3 Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Jobava Attack: 4.e4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. e4 { An attempt to impose sharp complications. } 4... cxd4
{ 4...dxe4  5.d5  is uncomfortable for Black. } 5. Nxd5 e5
{ Allowing Black to create a strong pawn center. } 6. Bd2 Be6
{ White can't ignore it. } 7. c4 Nf6 { Creating a small trap. } 8. Bg5 Nxd5
{ Black also attacks the g5-bishop with their queen. White has to take the queen, otherwise, they lose material. }
9. Bxd8 Bb4+ 10. Ke2 { 10.Qd2  loses material. } 10... Nf4+ 11. Kf3 Rxd8
{ Only two minor pieces for a queen, but how active these pieces are! } 12. a3
Be7 13. g3 h5
{ Black intends to play 14...Bg4 regardless of what white will play next. } 14.
h3 Bg4+ 15. hxg4 hxg4+ { White's rook is hanging on h1. } 16. Kxg4 Rxh1
{ Black gets a rook + knight to compensate the queen. Usually, it's not enough, but in this position, the enemy king's weakness and Black's piece activity are decisive. }
*

