1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. Nf3 { A logical developing move to support the center. } 4... Nf6 5. a3
{ To prevent Black from playing ...Bf8-b4 in future. } 5... e6 6. e3 a6
{ After white played 6. e3 they are threatening with 7. Nb5. Black needs to prevent it. }
7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bd3 Bd6
{ Not only to exchange the bishops, but to fight for the e5-square. } 9. O-O
O-O
{ Black intends to continue with ...e6-e5 controlling the center. However, please, make sure that ...e5-e4 works before you play it. For example,   10.Re1  e5  11.Bg3  and  11...e4  doesn't work because of  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.Bxe4  Nxe4  and  14.Nxe4  ,  the d5-pawn is pinned. }
