1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. Nf3 { A logical developing move to support the center. } 4... Nf6 5. e3 Bg4
{ With the idea to exchange Black's potentially bad light-squared bishop. } 6.
Bb5 e6 7. h3 Bxf3
{ Moving the bishop to h5 or f5 leads to  7...Bh5  8.g4  Bg6  9.Ne5  gaining more space on the kingside and pressuring the knight on c6. }
8. Qxf3 Qb6
{ 8...a6  is a possible alternative to simplify and equalize the position immediately. }
9. a4 Qa5
{ 9...a6  leads to  10.a5  after which Black has either to retreat and lose tempi or to sacrifice their queen for rook and bishop after  10...axb5  11.axb6  Rxa1+  12.Nd1  . That position is unclear. }
10. O-O a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ It is an equal position with good chances for both players. The place of action is mainly located on the queenside and on the c-file especially. Both sides are going to open it and enter the enemy camp. The presence of the white pawn on a4 makes the white queenside pawn structure weaker. If White pushes their c-pawn, they make the b2-pawn an object of the attack located on the semi-open file. }
*

