[White "4. 3.Nc3 Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Jobava Attack: 5...a6 (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. e3
{ In this variation, Black is able at least to equalize the position and get comfortable play. }
4... cxd4 { The most competitive move. } 5. exd4 a6
{ Another possible alternative for this position. Looks slow at first glance, but is flexible. Black defends against the Nb5 threat and wants to activate the bishop to g4... }
6. Nf3 Bg4
{ the main idea of the 5...a6 move. Black waited until White put the knight on f3. }
7. Be2 e6 8. O-O Rc8
{ The control over the c-file is vital to this position. Black intends to attack c2 or just occupy the c4-square with their knight. }
9. h3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Be7
{ Black intends to castle and finish their development. After that, they can pressure White's position and attack the weakness on c2. }
