1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. e3
{ In this variation, Black is able at least to equalize the position and get comfortable play. }
4... cxd4 { The most competitive move. } 5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bb5
{ Ambitious, but practically leads to all positions favoring Black. } 6... e6
{ In this position, the best set up for Black is: ...Nge7, ...Ng6, ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Rac8 & ...a6. }
7. Nge2
{ just a different setup. Of course, the knight on f3 is more helpful for White in this type of position. However, from e2 the knight can move to g3 and attack Black bishop on f5. }
7... Nf6
{ While White doesn't move their knight to e5 and the position doesn't require Black to support c6, it makes more sense to locate our kingside knight on f6. From f6, the knight may move to d7 and secure important squares - c5 and e5. }
8. O-O Be7
{ This time Black should develop their dark-squared bishop to e7 and keep the enemy dark-squared bishop on f4, because this bishop eliminates some of the e2-knight's prospects.   Moreover, there is no sense to fight for the e5-square, when White doesn't develop their knight to f3. We follow one of the basic chess strategies principles at the beginning of the game - to develop our minor pieces and then to castle. }
9. Bxc6+
{ In case of  9.Bd3  Black should retreat  9...Bg6  and capture with the h-pawn if White decides to exchange. }
9... bxc6 10. Na4 O-O
{ When one player gets the bishop pair, the best strategy for them is to open the position. }
11. Re1 Nd7 { The plan for Black is to play: ...Rc8, ...c5 & ...Bg6. } *

