4... cxd4 { The most competitive move. } 5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3
{ It's better to exchange rather than to lose a tempo and retreat. } 7. Qxd3 e6
{ There is no big difference between @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P1B2/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6  and  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P1B2/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf6  7...e6 is just more flexible. }
8. Nf3 Nf6
{ A typical Carlsbad Pawn structure with reversed colors. Black starts a pawn march on the queenside while White wants to occupy the e5-square with their pieces and maybe initiate a kingside attack. However, the knight on c3 looks quite suspicious. It's better to locate this piece on d2 to move to f3 and support the other knight on e5. }
9. Ne2 Bd6 { To exchange and simplify. } 10. c3 O-O 11. O-O Rb8
{ The position is equal and Black starts the Minority Attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 3.Nc3 Jobava Attack"]
[Black "Jobava Attack: 4.e3, 6.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ The Steinitz Counter-Gambit, or Jobava Attack named after Georgian Grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. This move has several ideas behind it: the main one is to play e2-e4, this knight also attacks the d5-square which allows White to push the d-pawn to d5 in a few lines.   And, of course, with 3. Nc3 White keeps in mind the idea of playing Nc3-b5 with a threat to fork on c7. Sometimes this threat limits Black's options. }
3... Nc6
{ With this move Black fights for the center and forces White to react because the d4-pawn is under attack. }
4. e3
{ In this variation, Black is able at least to equalize the position and get comfortable play. }
4... cxd4 { The most competitive move. } 5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3
{ It's better to exchange rather than to lose a tempo and retreat. } 7. Qxd3 e6
{ There is no big difference between @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P1B2/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6  and  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3p4/3P1B2/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nf6  7...e6 is just more flexible. }
8. Nf3 Nf6
{ A typical Carlsbad Pawn structure with reversed colors. Black starts a pawn march on the queenside while White wants to occupy the e5-square with their pieces and maybe initiate a kingside attack. However, the knight on c3 looks quite suspicious. It's better to locate this piece on d2 to move to f3 and support the other knight on e5. }
9. O-O { The most popular move for White. } 9... Be7
{ 9...Bd6  is still possible, but if Black plays for a win, it's better to keep more pieces on the board. }
10. Rfe1 O-O
{ Black reaches equality and they have a very simple plan: ...h6, ...Qb6, ...Rfc8, ...Qd8. The queen goes back to d8 allowing a pawn march on the queenside and supporting the kingside if needed. }
11. a3 h6 { Prophylaxis! Preventing a bishop or knight from going to g5. } 12.
h3 Qb6 { Moving the b-pawn means creating weaknesses on c2 & c3. } 13. Rab1
Rfc8
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Qd8, ...a6, ...b5 and to attack the queenside. }
*

