[Black "The Solid 3.c3: 2.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3
{ The position is likely to transpose to London System, however, White may even play something different. }
3... c5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. dxc5 e6
{ If Black captures on c5 with one tempo, the best White may get is an equal position. }
6. b4 a5 { A typical move to undermine these pawns. } 7. b5 Ne7
{ This position is better for Black as White is overextended on the queenside. You can check how the Avila Pavas, S. vs. Vera Siguenas game wenthere. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Solid 3.c3"]
[Black "The Solid 3.c3: 4.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. c3
{ This is actually the second most popular move. However, almost always this line is transposed to other London System variations with pawns on e3 and c3. }
3... Nc6
{ To control e5 and threaten ...Qd8-b6. Black also has the option to transpose into a semi-slav via  3...cxd4  . }
4. dxc5
{ A logical move when the pawn is on c3, but in this exact position, the bishop on f4 becomes the object of attack! }
4... e5 5. Bg3
{ 5.Be3  d4!  and White gets an almost losing position where they have to only defend! }
5... h5
{ Black has a strong center and the bishop on g3 is isloated from the game. }
6. h3 Nf6
{ 6...Bc5  looks good as well, but then White may play  7.b4  with a tempo and then even 8. b5 chasing our knight. }
7. b4 Ne4
{ We centralize our knight and want to take the bishop on g3 and to destroy the pawns structure. }
8. e3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 { The g3- & e3-pawns are now weaknesses. } 9... Qg5
{ A completely winning position for Black. The plan is to play: ...Be7, ...O-O & ...Be6. }
*

