1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. c3
{ This is actually the second most popular move. However, almost always this line is transposed to other London System variations with pawns on e3 and c3. }
3... Nc6
{ To control e5 and threaten ...Qd8-b6. Black also has the option to transpose into a semi-slav via  3...cxd4  . }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 { A typical move, but a mistake in this exact position. }
5... cxd4
{ The early ...cxd4 is usually good because Black doesn't let White play dxc5 & b4 and to create a counter-attack on the queenside. }
6. cxd4
{ In such positions, the queenside knight should be located on c3 - it has almost nothing to do on d2. That's why 5. Nbd2 was a mistake. }
6... Nh5
{ One of the typical ideas in the London system for Black is to attack the bishop on f4. }
7. Be5 f6 8. Bg3
{ Doesn't change much, but offers a better control over the e5-square for Black. }
