[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "4.Nf3, 5.Ne5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Ne5
{ Doesn't make much sense. This line is rare even among club players. The only idea is to play 6. Nc3 in case Black continues their development with 5...Qb6. In such a case, 6...Qxb2 is quite risky. }
5... e6
{ Another popular strategy against London System. This time it's even more effective compared to the ...Qb6  strategy. With 5...e6 move Black leaves their dark-squared bishop on c8 with the idea to support the queenside and the knight on c6. That's why, 5. Ne5 is almost useless. }
6. c3 Bd6 7. Nd2 Qc7 8. Ndf3
{ Reinforcing the knight on e5. This is where Black has 2 typical ideas: to play 8...Nd7 and exchange on e5 and simplify the position or to play 8...c4, focus on the queenside play and continue with ...a6 & ...b5. }
8... c4 9. Be2 b5
{ Black continues with ...a5 & ...b4. Even with the bishop on c8, this plan is good. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "4.Nf3, 5.Ne5?! #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Ne5
{ Doesn't make much sense. This line is rare even among club players. The only idea is to play 6. Nc3 in case Black continues their development with 5...Qb6. In such a case, 6...Qxb2 is quite risky. }
5... e6
{ Another popular strategy against London System. This time it's even more effective compared to the ...Qb6  strategy. With 5...e6 move Black leaves their dark-squared bishop on c8 with the idea to support the queenside and the knight on c6. That's why, 5. Ne5 is almost useless. }
6. c3 Bd6 7. Bb5 O-O
{ Black leaves the c6-knight without enough protection because of hidden tactical opportunities. }
8. Nxc6
{ I.  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Nd2  as an alternative to 9. Nxc6   9.Nxc6  Qc7  10.Bxd6  White may exchange bishops first or may retreat with the knight immediately.   10.Ne5  Rb8∓  Black is a pawn down, but has the bishop pair. ...Ba6 can be played to prevent White from castling.  10...Qxd6  11.Ne5  Rb8⩱  There is no bishop pair, but Black is still slightly better: better development and ...Ba6 again prevents White from castling.  12.Qc2  Qb6  to provoke 13.b3  13.b3  Ba6=∞  Black may focus on the attack on the queenside. The pawn on c3 becomes a weakness.  9...Qc7⩱  Black has the bishop pair. ..Rb8 provokes White to play b3 and weaken the pawn on c3.   II.  8.O-O  Qc7  provokes White to take on c6 or retreat with their knight to d3.  9.Nd3  c4⩱  And Black starts a pawn march on the queenside to create a weakness on c3. }
8... bxc6 9. Bxc6
{ 9.Bxd6  Qxd6⩱  Black is developed better and has two plans: to take on d4 and undermine the d4-pawn with the other c-pawn or just play ...e5 right away. }
9... Rb8
{ Black has an absolutely winning position. At least they capture the b2 pawn and activate their rook. There is also a chance to trap the white light-squared bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "Nf3 with Early Qc1: 7.cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. cxd4
{ Opens the c-file which can offer strong counterplay for Black after ...Bf5 & ...Rc8. }
7... Nh5 { Getting rid of the bishop on f4. } 8. Bg3 Bf5
{ No need to hurry and take the bishop on g3. } 9. Nc3 e6
{ The d5-pawn was hanging. } 10. Nh4
{ As White has weak light squares, White tries to exchange Black light-squared bishop. }
10... Bg6 11. Be2 Na5
{ A typical idea for Black in the Exchange Variation of the Slav Defense, but also works here @@StartBracket@@it's the same pawn structure@@EndBracket@@. The c4-square is a strong point for our knight. }
12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bh4 { Keeping their dark-squared bishop on the board. } 13...
Bd6 { To vacate the f8-square for the king in case of 14. Bb5  . } 14. O-O Rc8
{ Pressuring the c-file and reinforcing the c4-square as a future position for the knight. }
15. Qe1 Nf6 { 15...Qxb2  is a blunder due to  16.Nb5  and 17. Qxa5. } 16. Bg3
Bxg3 17. hxg3 Nc4
{ Or Nc6. The position is approximately equal but offers some activity on the queenside for Black. Moreover, there is no need to castle; Black may use the h-file to initiate the kingside attack. The position of the king in the center is preferable because White wants to exchange the queens and turn the game into an endgame. }
