[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. cxd4
{ Opens the c-file which can offer strong counterplay for Black after ...Bf5 & ...Rc8. }
7... Nh5 { Getting rid of the bishop on f4. } 8. Bg3 Bf5
{ No need to hurry and take the bishop on g3. } 9. Nc3 e6
{ The d5-pawn was hanging. } 10. Nh4
{ As White has weak light squares, White tries to exchange Black light-squared bishop. }
10... Bg6 11. Qd2
{ Because there is no knight on f6 that can attack the queen from e4, it's better for White to remove the queen from the c-file. }
11... Bb4 { The best place for our dark-squared bishop. } 12. Be2 Rc8 13. Rc1
Na5
{ The knight on a5 prevents white from playing a3 and also intends to occupy the c4-square. The plan for Black is to play: ...O-O, ...Nc4, double the rooks on the c-file and ...a6 to secure the b5-square. }
