[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "Nf3 with Early Qc1: 7.cxd4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. cxd4
{ Opens the c-file which can offer strong counterplay for Black after ...Bf5 & ...Rc8. }
7... Nh5 { Getting rid of the bishop on f4. } 8. Bg3 Bf5
{ No need to hurry and take the bishop on g3. } 9. Nc3 e6
{ The d5-pawn was hanging. } 10. Be2 Nxg3 11. hxg3 h6
{ After Nh4 our light-squared bishop escapes to h7. } 12. O-O Rc8
{ The best place for the rook is on the open files. And here the rook pins the knight on c3. }
13. Na4 Qc7 { Controlling the e5 square. } 14. a3 Bd6 15. b4
{ With two ideas: to support the c5-square and chase the knight. } 15... O-O
{ We have to finish our development and connect the rooks. } 16. Qd2 Nb8
{ With this move Black prepares ...b6 to chase the knight from c5 as well as covers the a6-square with their knight. }
17. Rfc1 Qe7
{ Of course, not  15...Qd7  . It falls under attack after  18.Nc5 } 18. Nc5 b6
19. Na6 Nd7 { And the White knight is locked on the edge of the board. } *

