1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. cxd4
{ Opens the c-file which can offer strong counterplay for Black after ...Bf5 & ...Rc8. }
7... Nh5 { Getting rid of the bishop on f4. } 8. Be5 f6 9. Bg3
{ Black can prepare their pieces and play e5, with a very strong center. } 9...
Bg4
{ 10.h3  cannot be played due to  10...Nxg3  11.fxg3  which ruins White's pawn structure and creates a weakness on g3. }
10. Be2 Nxg3 11. hxg3
{ In most cases, the bishop pair is always an advantage. } 11... O-O-O
{ The safest place for the king, given the semi-open h-file. } 12. Nc3 Kb8
{ The Black king is protected and we are ready to push e5 and open the position. }
