[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "Nf3 with Early Qc1: Avoid 11...Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. cxd4
{ Opens the c-file which can offer strong counterplay for Black after ...Bf5 & ...Rc8. }
7... Nh5 { Getting rid of the bishop on f4. } 8. Nc3 Nxf4 9. exf4
{ White is saddled with double f-pawns and an isolated d4-pawn. The plan for Black is simple - develop their pieces quickly. }
9... e6 10. Bb5
{ That's why I recommended playing ...e6, and keeping the bishop on c8. } 10...
Bd7 { Cements the position. } 11. O-O Nxd4
{ Leads to some complications that favor White. } 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Rd1 Qf6 14.
Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. Qc2
{ and the Black king is in trouble. I'm sure White can at least draw the game with a threefold repetition. }
