[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc1"]
[Black "Nf3 with Early Qc1: 7.exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1
{ One of the main ideas of this setup for White is to focus on the queenside and initiate a pawn march there after dxc5. This pawn march can be successfully supported with their queen on c1. }
6... cxd4
{ This move doesn't give a chance for the opponent to play their main plan - dxc5 and b4/a4 after that. This continuation offers at least equal positions for Black. }
7. exd4 Bf5
{ A typical Carlsbad pawn structure with reversed colors. Here it's better to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain. There is one thing a club player should learn about the bishop on f7 compared to bishop on c8 in London System. The bishop is almost always better on f5, but in case there is a weakness on b7 or a pin of the knight on c6 that requires additional support, the black light-squared bishop should stay on c8. }
8. Nh4 Be4
{ A typical move for the bishop after Nh4; we provoke f3 and then put the bishop on g6. }
9. f3 Bg6 10. Nd2 Rc8 { Threatening 11...Nxd4. } 11. Nb3
{ Supporting the d4-pawn. } 11... e6 12. Be2 a5
{ A useful move for Black with the idea of ...a4 and to put pressure on the queenside at a certain moment later in the game. }
13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Be3 { Supporting the d4-pawn } 14... Bd6
{ h2 is a weakness, but before you decide to capture this pawn, just make sure the bishop can escape afterwards... }
15. Qd2 Nd7
{ Black has a clear plan to continue their development and activate pieces: ...O-O, ...Rfe8, ...a4, ...e5, ...Na5 }
*

