{ A typical Carlsbad pawn structure with reversed colors. Here it's better to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain. There is one thing a club player should learn about the bishop on f7 compared to bishop on c8 in London System. The bishop is almost always better on f5, but in case there is a weakness on b7 or a pin of the knight on c6 that requires additional support, the black light-squared bishop should stay on c8. }
8. Be2 Rc8
{ Right now the d4-pawn is not hanging, but after this move, Black keeps in mind the idea of playing ...Nc6-b4-d3. }
9. O-O h6
{ Securing the bishop on f5. After that we have to finish our development: ...e6, ...Be7 & ...O-O  . }
10. Nbd2 e6
{ 10...g5 is a good alternative, but deserves detailed analysis. For example,  10...g5  11.Be5  Bg7  and the position is unclear. }
11. h3 Be7 12. a4 O-O
{ 12...g5  is a more aggressive alternative, but 12...O-O is the safest move. }
13. Bh2 Ne4
{ With several ideas: to exchange dark-squared bishops or to capture on d2 and occupy the b3- or c4-squares with the other knight. }
