[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qc2"]
[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qc2: 7.Nbd2, 8.dxc5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc2 g6
{ Please notice  6...Bf5  doesn't work. White should avoid  7.Qxf5  when Black, of course, captures the pawn and gains the rook after  7...Qxb2  & 8...Qxa1.   But instead of taking on f5 immediately, White should first play @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp2pppp/1qn2n2/2pp1b2/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PPQ2PPP/RN2KB1R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.dxc5  attacking the black queen. If  7...Qxc5  the bishop on f5 is hanging while the black queen no longer attacks b2. That's why Black has to capture the queen with  7...Bxc2  8.cxb6  axb6  and White is better, the position is open and they can successfully activate their light-squared bishop. 6...g6 makes more sense. Black wants to fianchetto and also keeps in mind to play ...Bc8-f5 later in the game. }
7. Nbd2 { This is the main line. } 7... Bg7 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. a4
{ This move is not dangerous for Black and simply they will finish their development which is quite important in the beginning of the game. }
9... O-O 10. a5
{ The idea of this move is to take the b6-square away, so the Black queen won't be able to retreat after 11.Nb3. And  10...Nxa5  is a complete blunder. Black loses this knight after the  11.b4  fork. }
10... e6 { Now Black queen escapes to e7. } 11. Be2 Nh5
{ Attacking the bishop. } 12. Nb3
{ 12.Bg5  allows Black queen to escape to d6 which is better than e7. } 12...
Qe7 13. Bg5 Nf6
{ Black intends to play 14...h6, 15...g5 and 16...Ne4 to attack the dark-squared bishop with their knight.   13...Qc7  is a good alternative. }
14. O-O h6 15. Bh4 a6
{ There is no need to hurry: 15...a6 stops white activity on the queenside. The plan for Black is to play: ...g5, ...e5 & ...Bd7. ...Ne4 can be also a part of that plan. While the enemy dark-squared bishop is restricted by the black pawns on g5 and e5, it's not necessary to trade it for our knight. }
