[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qb3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qb3: 7.Qxb6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qxb6 axb6
{ Doubling the pawns on the b-file only improves the black position. They get a clear plan and an open file. The endgame is preferable for Black and they have two strong plans: The first one is to put the bishop on f5 and to play ...h6 and the second one is to play ...e6 and ...Bd7. }
8. h3 b5
{ 8...Bf5  is a good alternative as well; White has to play with the b1-knight  9.Nbd2  and Black creates an escape square for that bishop with  9...h6  . }
9. g4 b4
{ A typical move in London system to grab some space on the queenside and create weaknesses in the enemy camp when the queens are exchanged. }
10. Bg2 e6 11. O-O b5
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...h6, ...Be7, ...Ne4 & ...Bd7 with a solid position. Black tries to pressure the weakness on c3, which is why White is likely to play cxb4. However, after ...Bxb4, Black intends to take the enemy knight on c3 and create a weak pawn on c3 that can be attacked with ...Ne4. As for the light-squared bishop on c8, right now it cements the black position on the queenside. However, one of the typical ideas here is to activate this bishop via d7-a4-c2. To be able to do it, Black often pushes their second b-pawn, because it's already a part of the plan. }
*

