1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qxb6 axb6
{ Doubling the pawns on the b-file only improves the black position. They get a clear plan and an open file. The endgame is preferable for Black and they have two strong plans: The first one is to put the bishop on f5 and to play ...h6 and the second one is to play ...e6 and ...Bd7. }
8. Ne5 Bf5
{ If possible, Black should always develop their light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain. }
9. Nd2 b5 10. Be2 h6 { To secure the light-squared bishop. } 11. g4 Bh7 12. O-O
{ And now we can switch the attack from the queenside to the kingside. } 12...
e6 13. a3 Be7
{ While the black king is not castled they have flexibility and can simply switch from one side to the other side of the board. The best squares for the black king are e7 or d7 in such a position. There are a lot of pieces on the board, but the position is closed and White won't be able to attack the black king with their rooks or minor pieces. }
14. f3 g5
{ One of the interesting plans for Black is to play ...g5, ...h5 and to focus their pieces on the kingside. }
15. Bg3 h5
{ The plan for Black is to play ...h4, ...Nd7, ...Bd6 and ...O-O @@StartBracket@@if the position is already closed on the kingside@@EndBracket@@. Please, also pay attention to white's activity; their main idea is to initiate e3-e4 and open the position. }
