[White "8. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qb3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qb3: 7.Qxb6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qxb6 axb6
{ Doubling the pawns on the b-file only improves the black position. They get a clear plan and an open file. The endgame is preferable for Black and they have two strong plans: The first one is to put the bishop on f5 and to play ...h6 and the second one is to play ...e6 and ...Bd7. }
8. Na3 Bf5 9. Nb5 Ra5
{ 10.Nc7+  only traps this knight. The plan for Black is to play: ...e6, ...Be7, ...Kd7 and to start an attack on the queenside. }
10. a4 e6
{ 10...Bc2  is an inaccuracy which allows White to continue their development and obtain some initiative as compensation for the a4-pawn. For example,  11.Be2  Rxa4  12.Kd2  and the h-rook joins the game.   If instead of 11...Rxa4 Black plays  11...Bxa4  White continues with  12.Nc7+  Kd7  13.Ng5  and the f7-pawn cannot be protected. }
11. Be2 Be7
{ The b2- and a4-pawns are the objects of the attack. Thegame Pakleza,Z - Kollars, D 0-1 2021 illustrates how Black converts their advantage in this position. }
12. Bc7 Ra6 13. O-O Kd7
{ There is no need to castle. The black king is pretty safe on d7, but also helps the other Black pieces. }
14. Ne5+ Nxe5 15. Bxe5
{ The a4 pawn is very weak and we focus our pieces to attack that weakness. }
15... Bc2 16. Bd1 Bxd1 17. Rfxd1
{ Black can't move the other rook to the a-file due to the Nc7 fork. That's why they have to change their plan and attack the a4-pawn later in the game! }
17... h5
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...h4, ...Ne8, ...f6, ...Nd6 to exchange knights and secure the c7-square & pressure the a4-pawn with ...Rha8. }
*

