{ A typical idea for White. } 18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 dxe4
{ in case of  20.Bxc4  White falls under a discovered attack. } 20. Bxc4 bxc3
{ To simplify first. } 21. bxc3 Nb4 22. cxb4 Qxd4
{ Black gains a minor piece back, but also captures a few pawns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 3.e3, 4.Nf3 with Early Qb3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 with Early Qb3: 7.Qc2, 9.h3 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qc2
{ The only other option.  7.Qa3  is a blunder due to  7...e5  attacking queen and bishop simultaneously. }
7... Bf5
{ If White takes this bishop  8.Qxf5  they lose the b2-pawn and the rook after  8...Qxb2  . }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qe2  blocks the bishop and  8.Qd2  fails to  8...Ne4  with a tempo. Black has to develop their pieces on the kingside. }
8... e6 9. h3 Be7 10. Nbd2
{ In this position there are two main options for Black: ...h6 - to protect their light-squared bishop or just ...O-O and let White exchange their knight for the black light-squared bishop. However, a deep analysis shows that O-O gives more chances for Black to win the game, while ...h6 is safer. You can play both options. }
10... O-O
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfc8, ...Qd8, ...b5 & ...b4 and to start an attack on the queenside. }
11. Be2 Rfc8
{ Black doesn't lose a tempo with ...h6 but immediately starts the plan. } 12.
O-O Qd8 { Vacating the b-file for the pawn march. } 13. Re1 b5
{ You can analyze the game between: Diaz,C - Atalik,S , 2014 , 0-1 that illustrates how Black should play and what to expect from White. }
14. Nh4 { 14.Bd1  was played in the game mentioned above. } 14... Be4
{ A typical idea for Black: ...Be4 and then ...Bg6. } 15. Nhf3 Bg6 16. Nh4
{ It's the same position, but Black saved a tempo. Black doesn't want to take the knight on f5, but is ok to take it with ...hxg6. }
16... b4 { We stick to our plan. } 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. e4
{ A typical idea for White. } 18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 dxe4
{ in case of  20.Bxc4  White falls under a discovered attack. } 20. Qe3 Qd5
{ Protects the pawns on e4 and c4. } 21. Bf1 a5 22. Qxe4
{ Black is ok to exchange the queens, but only if White takes. This is the way Black gets the c4-pawn protected and it may become a protected passed pawn later in the game. }
22... g5 23. Bg3 a4
{ With the idea of ...a3 which ruins the white pawn structure. } 24. a3 Qxe4
25. Rxe4
{ The endgame is slightly better for Black and without a counter-attack for White. }
25... bxc3 26. bxc3
{ Although White has the pair of bishops, the position for Black is still better and with more opportunities. }
26... Kf8 { The most important piece in the endgame is the king. } 27. Bh2
{ To play g4. } 27... Nb8
{ Black's knight wants to go to the d5 square and attack the weak pawn on c3. }
28. Ree1
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop for the knight in this position is not in White's favor. Their pawns on c3 and a3 become weaker. }
28... Nd7 29. Reb1 Nf6 30. g4 { To fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 30...
Nd5 31. Bg2 Ra7
{ Black gets rid of the pin and now White has to take that knight on d5. Otherwise, they lose their pawns on the queenside. }
32. Bxd5 exd5
{ After a lot of correct moves, White can have an equal position which is basically impossible for human beings to remember, so I believe that we should go through this line without thinking and hope that White makes a mistake along the way. }
*

