[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for White. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case, White opens the a-file and gets some activity. But 6...c4 forces White to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for Black. }
7. Qc2
{ The only other option.  7.Qa3  is a blunder due to  7...e5  attacking queen and bishop simultaneously. }
7... Bf5
{ If White takes this bishop  8.Qxf5  they lose the b2-pawn and the rook after  8...Qxb2  . }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qe2  blocks the bishop and  8.Qd2  fails to  8...Ne4  with a tempo. Black has to develop their pieces on the kingside. }
8... e6 9. h3 Be7 10. Nbd2
{ In this position there are two main options for Black: ...h6 - to protect their light-squared bishop or just ...O-O and let White exchange their knight for the black light-squared bishop. However, a deep analysis shows that O-O gives more chances for Black to win the game, while ...h6 is safer. You can play both options. }
10... h6
{ I don't recommend this move if you want to play for a win, however, this move allows your light-squared bishop to escape to h7. }
11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Rfc8
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Qd8, ...Bd6, ...b5 and continue the pawn march on the queenside. }
13. Re1 Qd8 14. Ne5 b5 { 13.Ne5  doesn't change our plan. } 15. Bf3
{ A typical move with the idea of e3-e4. } 15... Nxe5
{ Transposes to the main line -13.Re1 } 16. Bxe5 Bd3 17. e4 b4
{ White follows their plan and so does Black. } 18. Bxf6
{ Otherwise Black takes with this knight on d5. } 18... Bxf6 19. exd5 exd5
{ Black got a bishop pair and white tries to improve their worst piece. } 20.
Nf1 Rc6
{ A multifunctional move, however, the main idea is to protect the d5-pawn. }
21. Ne3 Rd6 { Protects the pawn on d5. } 22. g3 a5
{ Continuing the attack on the queenside. } 23. a3
{ 23.cxb4  axb4  creates a weakness for white on a2 @@StartBracket@@or a3@@EndBracket@@ }
23... bxc3 24. bxc3 Rb8 { Rooks are more powerful on the open files. } 25. a4
g6 { Prophylaxis. } 26. h4
{ White holds the position and it is very hard for Black to take any advantage. }
26... h5 27. Ra2 g5 { Another way to open up the position a little bit more. }
28. Rb2 { White exchanges their passive rook. } 28... Rxb2 29. Qxb2 gxh4 30.
Qb5
{ There is nothing Black can do to save the d5-pawn. And this pawn loss allows White to activate their pieces. }
30... hxg3
{ Black has the pair of bishops and weak pawns on d5 and h5 However, the position is still equal after  31.fxg3  . }
