[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for white. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case white opens the a-file and get some activity. But 6...c4 forces white to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for black. }
7. Qc2
{ The only other option. 7.Qa3 is a blunder due to 7...e5 attacking queen and bishop simultaneously. }
7... Bf5
{ If white takes this bishop 8.Qxf5 they lose the b2-pawn and the rook after 8...Qxb2 }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qe2 blocks the bishop and 8. Qd2 falls under 8... Ne4 with a tempo. Black have to develop their pieces on the kingside }
8... e6 9. Nh4 Be4 { The best response for Black after Nh4. } 10. Be2 h6
{ With the idea of ...g5 and ...Bh7. } 11. Nf3 Be7
