1. d4 d5 {  } 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and here white has 3 typical moves to protect the b2-pawn. }
6. Qb3 { This is the most common move for white. They offer an exchange. } 6...
c4
{ Black shouldn't take on b3. In this case white opens the a-file and get some activity. But 6...c4 forces white to either retreat or to exchange the queens. Both variations are favorable for black. }
7. Qc2
{ The only other option. 7.Qa3 is a blunder due to 7...e5 attacking queen and bishop simultaneously. }
7... Bf5
{ If white takes this bishop 8.Qxf5 they lose the b2-pawn and the rook after 8...Qxb2 }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qe2 blocks the bishop and 8. Qd2 falls under 8... Ne4 with a tempo. Black have to develop their pieces on the kingside }
8... e6 9. Nh4 Be4 { The best response for Black after Nh4. } 10. Nd2 Be7 11.
Be2 O-O { Black finishes their development. } 12. O-O Rfc8
{ Black follows the main idea in this position - ...Rfc8, ...Qd8. } 13. Nhf3
Bg6 { The plan for Black is to play: ...Qd8, ...b5, ...a5, ...b4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 3.e3 - The Tricky 5.Nbd2 (Without c3)"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.Rb1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. Rb1
{ The rook on b1 only has one function and has to stay there for a long time. Such a rook move is likely to result in a tempo loss. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 Nxd4 { White didn't have enough defenders of the d4-pawn. }
8. Nxd4 Qxd4 { Black won a central pawn and has an easy to play position. } 9.
Bb5+ { At least White tries to speed up their development. } 9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+
Nxd7 { And White doesn't have any ideas of how to develop their initiative. }
11. Be3 { This bishop was hanging. } 11... Qa4 12. O-O e6
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...Be7, ...O-O, ...Qc6, ...Nf6 & ...Rc8. They have a strong center and one extra pawn which gives Black clear chances to win the game. }
