[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. Qc1 { Leaving the d4-pawn unprotected. } 6... cxd4 7. exd4 Nxd4
{ Black is a pawn up with a better position. } 8. Be3
{ To create some complications and gain a tempo. } 8... Nxf3+ 9. Nxf3 Qd8
{ Black's queen is safe - all Black has to do is complete their development. }
10. Bd3 e6
{ It's better to keep the light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. First of all, this is how Black saves a tempo and castles faster. Second, this bishop covers any possible checks from b5. }
11. O-O Bd6
{ White has no compensation for the pawn they lost. The plan for Black is to play: ...O-O, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Re8 and to push the central pawns @@StartBracket@@e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ }
