[White "9. 3.e3 - The Tricky 5.Nbd2 (Without c3)"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. c3
{ Looks like a tempo loss. Black either wins the c3-pawn or the pawn should fight for the center and move to c4. }
6... Qxb2 7. Rb1 { Gaining a tempo, but letting Black capture the c3-pawn. }
7... Qxc3 8. Bb5 { At least trying to develop their initiative. } 8... Bd7
{ This bishop cements Black's position. } 9. O-O e6
{ Black has two extra pawns, but White has an advantage in development which is not enough to equalize the position. }
10. Ne5 Be7
{ Development should be a priority. In the case of   11.Nxd7  Black plays  11...Nxd7  . }
11. Ndf3 O-O
{ Black has a comfortable position because their king is not in danger anymore and the queen can escape from a5 to the d8 square and also they have a pawn majority on the queenside. Black is also two pawns up. The strategy for Black is to exchange a few pieces and to play on the queenside. }
