Qc1
{ Exchanging the queens. White wants to get rid of an attacker of the c5-pawn. }
15... Qxc1 16. Rfxc1 a5
{ Black intends to exchange bishops and occupy the center with the e-pawn. }
17. Nd4 Nxc5 { There is no better option - the c6-pawn can't be protected. }
18. Nxc6 e6
{ The black pawn structure looks better. However, Black has to spend a few tempos developing their pieces. The black bishop goes to d7 or b7 depending on what White plays. Generally speaking, the position is approximately equal, but practically Black has more winning chances due to their pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 3.e3 - The Tricky 5.Nbd2 (Without c3)"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.dxc5, 7.Bd3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Bd3
{ A possible, but slow move. White lost an important pawn on b2, their task is to develop the initiative as fast as they can. That's why 7. Rb1 is a more logical continuation. }
7... g6
{ Not the only possible response, but definitely the best one.  7...e6  or 7... Qc3 can be played as well. The idea of 7...g6 is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, pressure through the main diagonal and castle as soon as possible. However, this move is not well-studied and was played only once. The c5-pawn is a weakness and can be taken by the black queen. }
8. Nd4 a6
{ To secure the b5-square. The white knight on b5 also could restrict our queen activity. }
9. Rb1 Qa3
{ 9...Qc3 can be played as well, but   9...Qa2  is a critical mistake.  10.Ra1  attacking the queen,  10...Qb2  and  11.Nb5  ,  the a6-pawn is pinned, because of the open a-file. }
10. O-O Bg7
{ If only Black finishes their development, they will experience no problems at all. }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qc1 { To eliminate the attacker of the c5-pawn. } 12... Qc3
{ 12...Qxc5  allows White to obtain some initiative after  13.c4  . } 13. Nb3
{ Protecting the pawn. } 13... a5
{ With the idea to chase that knight and capture the c5-pawn. } 14. a4 e5
{ The position is materially equal, but Black controls the center while their queen is pretty safe. The c5- and a4-pawns are weaknesses. }
*

