[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 3.e3 - The Tricky 5.Nbd2 (Without c3)"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.dxc5, 7.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. c4
{ Another common response in this variation. White tries to open up the position and mobilize his pieces as fast as possible to be able to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
7... e6
{ Supporting the center.  7...Bf5  to prevent Ra1-b1 is a good alternative. However, in my opinion, it may be too risky to move the bishop outside the pawn chain too early. White can impose some complications with Bf1-b5 in future. }
8. cxd5 Nxd5 { Avoiding an isolani on d5. } 9. Rb1 Qxa2
{ Black threatens a fork with ...Nd5-c3 or just to capture the dark-squared bishop. }
10. Be5 Qa5 11. Bb5 Bd7
{ Threatening 12...Nxe5, which is why White has to take on c6. } 12. Bxc6 Bxc6
13. O-O
{ To bring the d2-knight to the attack, White should secure the king first. }
13... Be7
{ A very good practical move. Black has prepared a small trap after 14. Bxg7. }
14. Bxg7 Rg8
{ A kind of a positional trap, there are no concrete moves to defeat white immediately or take the g2-pawn, but Black gets a long-term positional advantage. }
15. Bd4 Nc3
{ The idea of the sacrifice on g7 is to win the bishop pair and to open the g-file. }
16. Ra1 { Intermediate move. } 16... Qb4 17. Bxc3
{ Otherwise, Black takes on c5 immediately. } 17... Qxc3
{ With a very promising position for Black. They have the pair of bishops and plan to promote a pawn on the queenside. If needed, Black can switch to the kingside and initiate a kingside attack. They intend to play ...Rd8, ...Rg4, ...Qd3, ...a5, ...a4 & ...Bf6. }
*

