{ 8...g6!?  also deserves attention but requires additional analysis. } 9. O-O
Be7
{ Important! Don't take the c5-pawn with your bishop. The c5-square is reserved for your queen. }
10. Nd4 Bd7 11. N2b3 { Supporting the c5-pawn. } 11... O-O 12. Bd3 Qb4
{ We have to escape with our queen very quickly. And there is now discovered attack on the b-file - no good spots for the b3-knight. }
13. c3 Qa4
{ In case of  13...Qxc3  White continues with  14.a3  and the queen gets trapped. }
14. Re1 a6
{ Black intends to attack White's pawn weaknesses. Their pawn structure on the queenside is ruined. The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfc8, ...Be8, ...Na7, ...Nb5. As for the black queen, every time the white knight leaves its position on b3, the queen gets the a5-square to escape. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 3.e3 - The Tricky 5.Nbd2 (Without c3)"]
[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.dxc5, 7.Rb1 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Rb1 Qc3
{ Not ...Qa2 - the black queen can get trapped there. And not ...Qa3 @@StartBracket@@which is actually possible@@EndBracket@@. Here on c3 the queen is more helpful. At least it pins the knight. }
8. Bb5 e6
{ 8...g6!?  also deserves attention but requires additional analysis. } 9. O-O
Be7
{ Important! Don't take the c5-pawn with your bishop. The c5-square is reserved for your queen. }
10. e4 O-O 11. e5 Nd7 { Both pawns are under attack. } 12. Nb3 Qb4
{ The f4-bishop is hanging. In case of  13.Bd2  our queen escapes to the kingside. No good spots to create a discovered attack. If only the b3-knight moves, Black captures the c5-pawn. }
13. Nfd4 { White is threatening 14. c3 and 15. Bd2 to trap our queen. } 13...
Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5 { The optimal spot for the queen in this variation. } 15.
Re1 a6
{ White can equalize the material balance if they play  16.Bxd7  Bxd7  17.Rxb7  ,  however, after  17...Ba4  Black obtains some initiative and keeps their bishop pair. If instead White decides to retreat to d3 with their bishop, Black has to continue 16... g6 to prevent a kingside attack. In this case, White will be a pawn down. You can see what happened then in the game between: Firouzja,A - So,W 1/2-1/2 2021. }
*

