[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Rb1 Qc3
{ Not ...Qa2 - the black queen can get trapped there. And not ...Qa3 @@StartBracket@@which is actually possible@@EndBracket@@. Here on c3 the queen is more helpful. At least it pins the knight. }
8. Bb5 e6
{ 8...g6!?  also deserves attention but requires additional analysis. } 9. O-O
Be7
{ Important! Don't take the c5-pawn with your bishop. The c5-square is reserved for your queen. }
10. Ne5 Bd7
{ Another alternative is  10...Qxc5  ,  but allows White to open the position with  11.c4  and the queen can be the object of attack. }
11. Nd3 O-O
{ If you want to play for a win, I suggest you play  11...b6  instead. It's riskier, but you don't allow White to repeat the position. }
12. Bc7 { After this move, our queen is in danger. } 12... Qa3 13. Rb3 Qxa2
{ The only move. } 14. Nc1
{ White has to make a draw by a threefold repetition. Otherwise, Black plays ...Rfc8, chases the bishop and escapes with their queen to a5. }
14... Qa1 15. Rb1 { Forcing a draw. } 15... Qc3 16. Rb3 Qa1 17. Rb1 Qc3
{ In this line we have to accept a draw. } *

