[Black "The Tricky 5.Nbd2: 6.dxc5, 7.Rb1 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ One of the most tricky options. White saves a tempo and doesn't play c3 but sacrifices the b2-pawn and tries to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
5... Qb6
{ And White loses one of these pawns. For example,  6.Nb3  is met by  6...c4  and Black still is able to win the b2-pawn. }
6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black.  6...Qxc5  leads to  7.a3  and 8. b4. In this case, White doesn't lose a pawn, but gains space on the queenside. }
7. Rb1 Qc3
{ Not ...Qa2 - the black queen can get trapped there. And not ...Qa3 @@StartBracket@@which is actually possible@@EndBracket@@. Here on c3 the queen is more helpful. At least it pins the knight. }
8. Bb5 e6
{ 8...g6!?  also deserves attention but requires additional analysis. } 9. O-O
Be7
{ Important! Don't take the c5-pawn with your bishop. The c5-square is reserved for your queen. }
10. Ne5 Bd7
{ Another alternative is  10...Qxc5  ,  but allows White to open the position with  11.c4  and the queen can be the object of attack. }
11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. e4
{ With the idea to open up the position and activate the knight. } 12... a6
{ Leads to a forced line with lots of only-moves. } 13. exd5 axb5
{ 13...exd5  14.Bxc6  bxc6  opens the e-file @@StartBracket@@which is in White's favor@@EndBracket@@ and allows the white rook to enter our camp with Rb1-b7. }
14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Ne4 { Attacking the queen and protecting the c5-pawn. } 15...
Qc4 { Attacking 2 minor pieces and the c5-pawn. } 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Qxd6
{ 17.Bxd6  leads to  17...Nxc5  . Then this knight comes to e4 to attack the d6-bishop. }
17... Qxc5 18. Qc7 Qb6
{ The endgame favors Black because of a better pawn structure. } 19. Qd6 c5
{ If you want to play for a win. Castling is our first priority, so we must get rid of the enemy queen. }
20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. Rxb5
{ White has to capture on b5, otherwise Black plays ...b4. } 21... Nd5 22. Be5
O-O
{ With an approximately equal endgame. White has weaknesses on c2 and a2 and it could be a good chance for Black to attack them and play for a win. Moreover, the d5-knight is located pretty well on d5 and is not worse than the enemy bishop on e5. The plan for Black is to play: ...f6, ...Nb4 and ...Rfd8. }
