[White "10. 3.e3 - Bishops Before Knights - 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Bishops Before Knights: 6.Qc1, 7.cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3
{ This is a different move order which allows White to save a tempo on a knight move, but develop the bishop to prevent Black from playing ...Bf5. However, this move has its own disadvantages which I will illustrate. }
5... Qb6 { Same idea - to attack the b-pawn. } 6. Qc1
{ The most popular move. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nb4
{ And White has to let Black exchange their knight for the light-squared bishop. }
8. Be2 Bf5 9. Na3 { The only way to defend the c2-square. } 9... Rc8 10. Qd1
Bc2 11. Qd2 Ne4 { The queen is almost trapped. } 12. Qc1
{ The queen finally escaped to the only safe place, but White falls under a tactical strike! }
12... Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 Qb4+ { And White king has to move to a light-square. } 14.
Ke2 { Is even worse than 14. Kf1  . } 14... Bxd3+ 15. Kxd3 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qd2# *

