[White "10. 3.e3 - Bishops Before Knights - 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Bishops Before Knights: Avoid 11...Nc2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3
{ This is a different move order which allows White to save a tempo on a knight move, but develop the bishop to prevent Black from playing ...Bf5. However, this move has its own disadvantages, which I will illustrate. }
5... Qb6 { Same idea - to attack the b-pawn. } 6. b3 Bg4
{ Black wants to develop their light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain. }
7. Nf3 Nh5
{ Definitely stronger than  7...e6  or  7...cxd4  and a blitz match FM Nikolay Yordanov - FM Viktor Neustroev proves it! }
8. Be5 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nb4
{ Black is about to exchange both knights for enemy bishops. } 10. Be2 Rc8 11.
O-O Nc2 { unfortunately doesn't work! } 12. Nc3 Nxa1
{ If  12...Rxc3  13.Rc1+  wins back the piece for White. } 13. Bb5+
{ an intermediate check forcing our king to move. } 13... Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7
15. Nxd5 Qc6 16. Ng5
{ White's initiative compensates the material they sacrificed.... } 16... Qxd5
17. e4 Qc6 18. Qg4+ *

