[Black "The Passive b3 Setup: 4.Nf3, 7.exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. b3
{ Definitely not the strongest option. That's why it is mainly played only at the club level.  6.Qb3  ,  6.Qc2  &  6.Qc1  are more common. }
6... cxd4 { The most effective way to prove that this is a mistake. } 7. exd4
Bf5 8. Bd3
{ White has to exchange light-squared bishops. The one on f5 is better. } 8...
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 { And Black continues their development. } 10. O-O Be7
{ The position is equal and White has to come up with a strategic plan. } 11.
c4 Ne4
{ 11...dxc4  is another possible option.  12.bxc4  ,  White gets hanging pawns that do not particularly restrict Black's pieces. One pair of minor pieces is already removed from the board. }
12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc3 Nxc3 { 13...Nb4  gains a tempo, but it's not required. }
14. Qxc3 O-O
{ The pawn structure is symmetrical and the position is equal. However, practically Black should have more chances to succeed. The pawn on d4 is weaker than the one on d5. And that can be a decisive factor. }
