1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. b3
{ Definitely not the strongest option. That's why it is mainly played only at the club level.  6.Qb3  ,  6.Qc2  &  6.Qc1  are more common. }
6... cxd4 { The most effective way to prove that this is a mistake. } 7. exd4
Bf5 8. Bd3
{ White has to exchange light-squared bishops. The one on f5 is better. } 8...
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 { And Black continues their development. } 10. O-O Be7
{ The position is equal and White has to come up with a strategic plan. } 11.
h3 Rc8
{ The pawn on c3 is a permanent weakness. That's why top players actually avoid this variation and don't play 6. b3 }
12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Rfe1 a5
{ Just to illustrate what happens if White doesn't show any activity on the queenside. }
14. Re3 Rfd8 15. Rae1 Qa6 { Exchanging queens and opening files. } 16. Qxa6
bxa6
{ Black has doubled a-pawns, but open the files on which to attack enemy pawns on the queenside. }
17. Kf1 a4
{ With pressure on the open files. In case of  18.bxa4  Black is able to gain the pawn back after  18...Nd7  With Nb6-a4 to follow. }
