[White "12.  3.e3 - 5.Nd2 Mainline (Before Nf3)"]
[Black "Early Nd2 Mainline: 6.Ngf3, 7.Qb3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 e6
{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. Qb3 Qc8
{ With this move we keep the position more complicated.  7...Qd7  fails to  8.Ne5  with Bf1-b5 ideas. }
8. c4 a5
{ 8...cxd4 deserves attention and is playable among grandmasters as well as the 8...a5 that I recommend. The idea of such a move is to chase enemy queen away. }
9. Qa4 { Blocking the a-pawn and pinning the knight on c6. } 9... cxd4
{ To open up the bishop on f8 } 10. Nxd4
{ 10.exd4?!  Bb4  In several lines Black takes the advantage of the pin on d2. That's why, White has to get rid of the pin immediately.  11.a3  Bxd2+  12.Bxd2  The f3-knight protects on d4.  12...dxc4  Otherwise, White plays 13.c5 and dominates on the queenside.  13.Bxc4  White agrees to play with an isolated pawn  13...O-O  14.O-O  Be4⩲  The d4-pawn is a weakness here and White's bishop pair doesn't compensate it. Black's plan is to activate pieces and pressure the d4-pawn. }
10... Bb4 11. Rd1 { securing the other knight on d2. } 11... O-O 12. Nxf5
{ White is forced to take, otherwise Black captures on d4 @@StartBracket@@there is no pin on c6 anymore@@EndBracket@@ and creates an isolated pawn which later becomes the object of the attack. }
12... exf5
{ 12...e5!?  Another playable option. With this double attack Black gains a minor piece back. }
13. a3 { Black was threatening with 13...Ne4 } 13... Bxd2+ 14. Rxd2 d4
{ opening white king's position } 15. Bd3
{ to speed up castling   15.exd4  Re8+  Activating a rook and taking the e-file under their control  16.Be2  16.Re2 loses the d4-pawn.  16...Re4  17.Be5  17.Be3 - just 17...f4  17...Nxe5  18.dxe5  Rxe5=  The position is equal. White castles on the next move, but they are unable to take the advantage of their queenside pawn majority. Black pieces activity is a more decisive factor. }
15... dxe3 16. fxe3
{ 16.Bxe3  falls under a forced combination  16...f4  17.Bxf4  the idea was to attract the bishop to f4  17...Qg4  18.Bg3  Rfe8+  White can't block this check, Black just adds more pressure or exchange white rook on d2.  19.Kf1  Rad8-+  Black centralized their pieces, while White rook is locked on h1 and other pieces lost their coordination. }
16... Qe6
{ Black's plan is to attack the weakness on e3, activate rooks and occupy key-squares such as e5 & e4 with their knights. }
