[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 e6
{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. Qb3 Qc8
{ With this move we keep the position more complicated.   7...Qd7  fails to  8.Ne5  with Bf1-b5 ideas. }
8. c4 a5
{ 8...cxd4 deserves attention and is playable among grandmasters as well as the 8...a5 that I recommend. The idea of such a move is to chase enemy queen away. }
9. dxc5
{ White wants to open up the c-file and avoid getting an isolated pawn on d4. }
9... Bxc5 10. cxd5 Nxd5
{ 10...exd5  makes the d5-pawn the object of White's attack. } 11. Bg3 a4
{ This was the original idea of 8...a5. } 12. Qc4 Ra5
{ Protecting the bishop and keeping in mind future activity of this rook on the 5th rank. }
13. e4
{ A move that wins a piece at first glance.   13.Be2  just continuing pieces development  13...Nb6  14.Qc1  O-O  White underestimating the black rook maneuver. Black doesn't need to move the queen to release the rook - now the a-rook goes to c5 which allows Black to get control over this file! }
13... Bg6 14. exd5 exd5 { White is temporary a piece up. } 15. Qf4
{ 15.Qe2+  Interesting, but weak move.  15...Kd8  Threatening the pin on the e-file.  16.Qd1  Re8+  17.Be2  And now Black takes the advantage with this pin.  17...Bd3  18.Ne5  There is nothing else to suggest for White. They should somehow block the e-file then castle.  18...Nxe5  19.O-O  Now White has successfully castled, but is a pawn down.  19...Bxe2  20.Qxe2  Qg4  White has to exchange the queens or allow Black to develop the initiative. In both cases, they can't take advantage of the black king position on d8. }
15... Qe6+ 16. Be2
{ 16.Kd1  The king in the center becomes the object of attack.  16...O-O  17.a3  Re8  Black's attack compensates for a minor piece sacrifice. It's difficult to suggest a move for White, while Black intends to play ...Bd4 & ...Rc5 to threaten c2. }
16... Bd3 { Taking the advantage of the pin immediately. } 17. O-O
{ 17.Ng1  defends the bishop, but allows Black to maintain the pressure on e2. }
17... Bxe2 18. b4
{ To distract the bishop.   18.Rfe1  O-O  White can't take the advantage of the pin and Black is going to advance the d-pawn to d3. }
18... Bxb4 19. Nd4 Bxd2
{ To distract the queen from f4. White was threatening Qb8 in case Black's knight on c6 moves. }
20. Qxd2 Nxd4 21. Qxd4 O-O
{ Black is 2 pawns up and White can't take advantage of the pin on the e-file. }
