1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 e6
{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nd4
{ A logical move for White, centralizing the knight on d4. One interesting game in this position is between: Raznikov,D - Xiong,J 2017, 0-1. }
8... Bg6
{ Almost every time in the London System if we have a chance to save the bishop pair, we'd better do it! }
9. N2b3 Bd6 { We want to save our bishops. } 10. Bb5 O-O 11. Bxc6
{ Winning a pawn. } 11... bxc6 12. Nxc6
{ White is a pawn up but Black took the initiative. } 12... Qc7 13. Nba5 Rfc8
14. O-O { White's knights are redundant. } 14... Bxf4 15. exf4 Kh8
{ Avoiding the Ne7+ fork. The plan for Black is to play ...Qb6 or ...Qf4, ...Ne4, ...Bd3 if it is possible, and attack on the queenside. }
