1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 e6
{ In this position, White has 8 main responses where we have to play very carefully and properly if we want to have a nice and easy position to play. }
7. Bb5 Qb6
{ The pin is very dangerous for Black, which is why we want to remove the bishop from b5. }
8. Qa4 { Ne5 is coming. } 8... a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. c4 Be7
{ We have to develop our pieces. } 11. O-O O-O 12. dxc5
{ 12.Ne5  fails to  12...Qxb2  ,  which is in Black's favor - the d2-knight is hanging as well. }
12... Bxc5 13. Rac1
{ White puts the rook on the semi-open file and puts pressure on the c6 pawn. }
13... Rfc8 14. Nb3 Bf8
{ Saving the bishop pair and our plan is to play ...c5, ...a5, ...Qb4, ...Qb5 @@StartBracket@@exchanging the queens is better for us because in the endgame, the pair of bishops is a very powerful weapon@@EndBracket@@. }
