[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Chernyshov, K. vs. Solodovnichenko, Y. - 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Here is a Model Game forchapter 1 where White plays a weird 3rd move, gets an inferior position and as a result, loses the game. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Bxb8
{ From a strategic point of view, this move is not good because White exchanges their active piece for the inactive black one. }
3... Rxb8
{ There are not so many games in this variation but is very important to see how Black takes advantage of this position. }
4. c3 cxd4 { Thecourse recommends  4...Nf6  but this is a good alternative. }
5. cxd4 Qb6 { A typical move for Black in London System. } 6. Qb3 Qxd4
{ Taking the pawn on d4 is not dangerous for Black which is why they are taking that gift. }
7. e3 Qc5 8. Bb5+
{ White's main idea was to activate their bishop and force Black to move the king. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Kxd7
{ The king is in the center during a middlegame but there is no danger for the black king. Also, this position reminds of one very famous game between Kasparov, G - Karpov, A, played a long time ago. }
10. Nc3 e6
{ Black protects their d5 pawn and opens the diagonal for their bishop. } 11.
Nf3
{ 11.Qa4+!?  Kd8  The plan for Black is to play: ...Bd6, ...Nf6, ...Ke7, ...Rhc8 and we will receive a similar position to the game.  12.Nf3  Bd6⩱  There is not enough compensation for the pawn White sacrificed.  13.O-O  Nf6  14.Rac1  The most logical move for white - to activate their passive rook and create some tactical threats.  14...Qb4!  Black is a pawn up and exchanging queens favors them.  15.Qxa7  Ke7⩱  After ...Ra8, ...Qd4, ...Rhc8 Black will have a slightly better endgame. }
11... Bd6 { Controlling the e5 square. } 12. O-O Nf6
{ It is time to activate the other passive pieces on the board. } 13. Nb5 Rhc8
{ We need our rooks on open files. Black keeps in mind the idea of exchanging their queen for two rooks. }
14. Qa4
{ 14.Nxd6  Kxd6∓  Black's king is surrounded by pawns, minor pieces, and major pieces and feels very comfortable in the middle of the board. }
14... Qc4
{ One very important rule - when we have a material advantage we have to exchange some pieces. }
15. Qxc4 Rxc4
{ Wining position for Black because they are a pawn up, control the center and the c-file. }
16. Ng5 { 16.Nxa7  Rb4-+  And Black gains the pawn back or traps the knight. }
16... Rf8 17. Nxa7 h6 18. Nf3 Rb4 { Black wants to take the knight on a7. } 19.
a3 Rxb2 20. Rfb1 Rxb1+ { Every exchange is better for Black. } 21. Rxb1 Rb8 22.
Nb5 Ne4 { Black has to play with all the pieces on the board. } 23. g4 Ra8
{ The a3 pawn is the main target for Black. } 24. h4 Ra4 25. Kg2 Nc5 26. g5 h5
{ White gets another weakness. } 27. Nfd4 Be5 28. Nf3 Bb8 29. Nfd4 e5
{ After this, Black has a completely winning position with which most players can win very easily. }
30. Nf5 g6 31. Nh6 Ke6 32. Nc3 Ra6 33. Rd1 Rxa3 34. Nxd5 Rd3 35. Rxd3 Nxd3 36.
Nc3 f6 37. Kf1 Nc5 38. Nb5 fxg5 39. hxg5 Ne4 40. f4 exf4 41. Nd4+ Kd5 42. Nf7
fxe3 43. Nf3 Nd2+
{ Black exchanges the knights and then captures the g5 pawn. This game illustrates that such weird moves as 3...Bxb8 don't offer any advantage for White and even if the black king loses its castling privileges, a strong pawn center more than compensates. }
