[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Astaneh Lopez, A. vs. Shirov, A. - 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4 { Covered inChapter 2. } 3... dxe4 4. d5 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
6. Qe2
{ Intending to capture the central pawn. The main lines in this position are 6. Qd2, 6. Nb5 and 6. f3  . }
6... Bg7 7. O-O-O { 7.Nxe4  immediately loses the pawn on d5. } 7... O-O 8. f3
{ A typical move which we can see in many variations. } 8... exf3 9. Nxf3
{ Black is a pawn up, but White has an advantage in development. However, it's not enough to compensate for a pawn. }
9... Bg4
{ This move is not very logical because after h3 Black has to give up their light-squared bishop.   9...Nbd7!?  10.g3  Qa5  Black has to focus their pieces to the queenside.  11.Kb1  Nb6-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Bf5, ...Na4 & ...Rad8. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3
{ This position is very dynamic because of opposite castling. The plan for both sides is very easy - to attack the enemy king. The advantage for Black is that they are a pawn up and the advantage for White is that the position is open and they have the bishop pair. }
11... Nbd7
{ Black has to develop their pieces very quickly because after g4 & h4, White starts to attack the king first. }
12. d6
{ 12.Kb1  This move is always useful when there is long-castling.  12...Qa5  13.g4⇆  13...Ne8  to get to d6 and avoid g5 with a tempo  14.h4  Bxc3  15.bxc3∞  The position is unclear. And the player who attacks faster usually wins. }
12... e6
{ There is no need to open the position. It's in White's favor because of the bishop pair. Moreover, Black successfully blockades the d6-pawn. }
13. h4
{ The best move for White. They start an immediate attack on the kingside. Also, h4 is a very typical way to destroy the pawns h7-g6-f7. }
13... Nh5
{ 13...h5  In 99% of cases after h4, the best response for Black should be ...h5. }
14. Bg5 Bf6
{ 14...Qa5  The queen joins the queenside to start the attack on the enemy king.  15.Kb1⩲  c4⇆  A position to play for 3 results. Plans for both players are obvious. }
15. Ne4 { Inviting Black to capture on g5. } 15... Bxg5+ 16. hxg5
{ White may either sacrifice the rook on h5 or just play g4 to open the h-file. }
16... f5 17. Bc4
{ Now a completely winning position is absolutely losing for White. It's not a good idea to create complications when you already have a nice position.   17.gxf6  Nhxf6  The protection of the Black king is destroyed and after Qh3, Bc4, Ng5 White will start a monster attack. }
17... fxe4
{ White miscalculated - there is no compensation for the piece they sacrificed. }
18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Qc3+ Ng7 { Knights are the best defenders of the king. } 20.
Qg3 { Giving up the bishop. } 20... Nxe6 21. Rxh7+ { Just a bluff. } 21... Kxh7
{ After a lot of sacrifices, White has nothing and Black has very easily winning position. }
22. Qh3+ Kg8 23. Qxe6+ Kg7 24. Kb1 Qe8 25. Qg4 Qf7 26. Qh3 Rh8 27. Qc3+ Kg8 28.
b3 Re8
{ Black made several mistakes which lead to a loss, however, I emphasized critical points where Black could play better and obtain the advantage. 3. e4 is good for blitz games. But with a longer time control, Black proves that the advantage is on their side. }
