[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fries Nielsen, N.J. vs. Semcesen, D. - 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. dxc5
{ White is with a pawn up but they give up the center. The early dxc5 lines are covered inchapter 3. }
4... e6
{ Very strong players who play this line for Black are: Dubov, D; Ding, L; Gelfand, B; Bluebaum, M. }
5. Nbd2
{ 5.b4  a typical move to save the pawn doesn't work here. Black captures it anyway.  5...a5  6.Nbd2  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  8.cxb6   8.Nb3  Na6  9.a3  fails because of  9...Nxb4  .  8...Bxb4  9.Rb1  Qxb6  10.a3  White can't take advantage of the pin.  10...Bxd2+  11.Bxd2  Qc7  12.Bb4  doesn't prevent Black from casting. After 12. ..Na6 White has to tolerate the weakness on a3 and should focus on their piece-development. }
5... Bxc5 6. Nb3
{ The position favors Black because they gain the pawn back and may control the center later in the game. }
6... Bb6 7. Bf4 Nc6
{ Both sides follow one of the main rules of how to play the opening - 'Develop the minor pieces rapidly'. }
8. e3 O-O
{ The main idea for Black is to play ...e5 and to control the center. } 9. h3
Qe7
{ One of the best squares for the queen from which it supports the e-pawn. }
10. Be2
{ 10.Ne5  to prevent ...e6-e5  10...Ne4  with ...f6 on the next move   or  10...Nd7  11.Nxd7  White can't prevent Black from playing ...e5.  11...Bxd7  12.Bg3  Rad8  13.Be2  f5  A good alternative to a standard plan with ...e6-e5. Black may initiate a kingside attack and expose their king - they have several pieces around it. That's why the king is safe.  14.O-O  g5∓  continuing the attack on the kingside. }
10... e5
{ After this move, Black controls the center and opens the diagonal for their light-squared bishop. }
11. Bh2 Bf5 { Black reaches their goal of pushing the e5-pawn. } 12. O-O Rad8
{ It's time to improve the rooks. } 13. Bb5 Bc7
{ 13...Nd7  as an alternative to 13...Bc7  14.Qxd5??  that was a poisoned pawn.  14...Nc5  15.Bxc6  The best thing White can do - just to give up the queen.  15...Rxd5  16.Bxd5-+  Black has extra material and an absolutely winning position. }
14. Re1 a6
{ The bishop on b5 looks active and a little bit dangerous which is why Black wants to remove it from the board. }
15. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Black has the bishops, strong center, and a very nice position.. } 16. Qe2
Ra8
{ 16...a5!  typical move for Black, with one pawn we can destroy the White's pawns structure on the queenside  17.c4  a4!  18.Nbd2  Rfe8-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Bb8, ...Qb7 & ...Ne4. }
17. c4 a5 18. cxd5
{ 18.Rac1!?  Another interesting alternative. It is not necessary for White to take on d5. They may activate the rook.  18...Bd6  With this move, Black controls the e5 and c5 squares which are very important in this position.  19.Red1  White improves the position of their rook.  19...a4!  We follow our idea to play ...a5-a4.  20.Nbd2  h6∓  Prophylaxis. One simple move with three ideas: ...Kh7, ...Bh7, and ...g5!?. The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfe8, ...Ra5, ...Qb7 & ...Ne4. }
18... cxd5 19. Rac1 { Rooks are more powerful on open files. } 19... Rfc8
{ The only piece for Black which is not playing is already active. } 20. Rxc7
{ An interesting idea for White is to sacrifice an exchange, to take one of the central pawns from Black and to find nice squares in the center for their knights.   20.Nc5⩱  A better option for White after which Black is still better.  20...Bd6  21.Na4  Re8  Black has one very aggressive plan: ...Qb7, ...h6, ...g5 and to open the position on the kingside. }
20... Rxc7 21. Bxe5 Rcc8
{ 21...Rc2?!  22.Qd1  ...Rc2 is not so good because after Nd4 white can win a piece and Black has to move their rook back to c8.   22.Qb5  22...Rcc8∓   21...Rc4!?  22.Bc3  Another interesting idea for White is to transfer the bishop from h2-b8 diagonal to a1-h8 diagonal.  22...a4  23.Nbd4  Bd7  The bishop restricts the opponent's knight to jump on f5 and b5 square.  24.Nd2  Rcc8  The plan for Black is to play: ...h6, ...Ne4, ...Qc5, ...Rb8 and slowly improve their position. }
22. Nbd4 Bd7 23. Bf4 Ne4
{ Black wants to centralize and activate their knight. } 24. Nd2 h6
{ Prophylaxis. ...h6 is always good when it comes to an endgame. } 25. N2f3 a4
{ Step by step, Black improves their position.   25...g5!?  This move looks very interesting. Because we have a pair of bishops, two rooks, and a better position, we can afford to play on both flanks.  26.Bh2  g4!  27.hxg4  Bxg4  With some pressure on the kingside. }
26. Ne5 Ra5 27. f3 Nf6
{ 27...Nd6!  The idea of that move is to play ...Nf5 or ...Nb5 and in the right moment to take the knight on d4.  28.Nd3  Nf5∓  to get rid of a perfectly located knight on d4. }
28. g4
{ White takes control of the f5-square but in this way, the king gets exposed. }
28... Rac5
{ 28...Ne8!  Probably the only winning plan - with the idea ...Nd6, ...Nb5 and ...f6.  29.Kg2  Nd6  30.Qd2  Ra7  The knights on e5 and d4 look very strong and Black has to take one of them also if they follow one basic rule ' If we have a material advantage we have to exchange pieces' Black will succeed in this game.  31.Nxd7  Qxd7∓  The plan for Black is to play: ...f6, ...Nb5, ...Rac7, ...Rc2 and to attack the opponent. }
29. Qd2 Be6 { 29...Bb5!? } 30. Nd3
{ White created something like a fortress in the center. } 30... Rc4 31. Ne5
R4c5 32. Nd3 Rc4 33. Ne5 R4c7 34. Bg3 Rb7 35. Nd3 Qd8 36. b4 axb3 37. axb3
{ White creates a passed pawn on the queenside. } 37... Qb6 38. Bf2 Qd6 39. Kg2
Qa3 40. h4 Qe7 41. Nf4
{ Black didn't win this game because they couldn't find the right plan which can destroy the fortress. At move 28 we can find some interesting lines for Black which could break the wall. }
