[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Nc3
{ Steinitz Counter-Gambit, orJobava Attack named after Georgian grandmaster, Baadur Jobava. }
3... Nc6 4. e3
{ In this variation, Black is able at least to equalize the position and get comfortable play. }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nf3 Nf6
{ A typical Carlsbad Pawn structure with reversed colors. Black starts a pawn march on the queenside, White wants to occupy the e5-square with their pieces and maybe initiate a kingside attack. However, the knight on c3 looks quite suspicious. It's better to locate this piece on d2 to move to f3 and support the other knight on e5. }
9. Ne5
{ A typical and logical move for White in the London system. Other possible options for White are: O-O, a3 & Qb5. This is the first deviation from thecourse. }
9... Be7 { Black wants to finish their development. } 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne2
{ 11.Nxc6!?  bxc6  12.Na4=  Black tries to take control over the e5- and c5-squares.  12...Qa5  13.b3  Rac8=  The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfe8, ...Ne4 & ...Bd6. }
11... Rc8 { Black wants to play ...Nb4 and win a pawn. } 12. c3
{ In this typical pawns structure, Black can start to attack on the queenside playing ...b5, ...a5, ...b5, and White intends to play f4 & f5. }
12... Nxe5
{ One of the most popular ideas for Black is to play ...Ne5 and then ...Bd6. }
13. Bxe5
{ 13.dxe5!?  Ne4!  Of course, knights always feel comfortable in the center.  14.Rac1  Re8  The plan for Black is to play: ...Qc7, ...a6, ...f6!?, ...Qc4. }
13... Bd6 14. Rae1 a6 { With the idea of ...b5. } 15. Ng3 Rc6 16. Re2
{ These maneuvers for White don't change the equal evaluation of the position. }
16... b5
{ Black is trying to do something on the queenside, sticking to the plan. } 17.
Rd1 Bxe5 18. dxe5
{ 18.Rxe5?!  Qb8  19.a3  a5∓  After ...Rfc8, ...b4 Black will start a Minority Attack on the queenside. }
18... Nd7 { Black has a very nice c4 square for their rook on the queenside. }
19. Qe3 Qe7 20. a3 Rfc8 { Black transfers all their pieces to the queenside. }
21. Rd4 g6
{ Black wanted to secure the king and created an escape square. However, instead they'd better play ...h6 or even postpone kingside pawns moves, but continue playing on the queenside.   21...a5!  22.Re1  Rc4!  23.h3  b4⩱  After h6, axb4, bxc3 White gets a weak pawn on c3. }
22. h4 h5
{ A typical response after h4 after which the position becomes equal. } 23. Qf4
Rc4 24. Re3 Rxd4
{ 24...a5!?  This plan could practically offer some winning chances for Black. }
25. cxd4 Nf8
{ A passive move for Black.   25...a5!?  Looks like Black for some reason refused the idea of playing ...a5 and as a result ended up in a draw. }
26. Re2 Rc4 27. Nf1 Qa7 28. Rd2 Rc1
{ This is where both players agreed to a draw, despite the fact that Black was slightly better. Generally speaking, in this variation Black equalizes the position in the first ten moves and after that, they should initiate counterplay on the queenside but it is very important to exchange a few minor pieces and to stick to the plan because with a few minor pieces White is unlikely to find a plan to get something going on the kingside. }
