[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Avila Pavas, S. vs. Vera Siguenas, D.A. - 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. c3 { Such setups are covered inchapter5. }
4... Nc6 5. dxc5 e6 { Intending to capture on c5 with the bishop. } 6. b4 a5
{ A typical move with the a-pawn is to destroy the white pawns on the queenside. }
7. b5 Ne7 { That position is better for Black as shown in thecourse. } 8. Ne5
{ Probably to prevent Black from playing  8...Ng6  . } 8... Ng6 9. Nxg6 hxg6
{ White has an extra pawn, but they lose it in the next few moves. } 10. Qd4
{ 10.c6!?  White loses that pawn anyway, so another option is to push the c-pawn.  10...Ne4  threatening 11...Qf6 to attack the bishop, the c3- and f2-pawns.  11.Nd2  Nxc3  12.Qc1  Nxb5∓  The plan for Black is to play ...Na3, ...Bb4, ...Bxb7, ...Rc8 with easy play. }
10... Ne4 { Black centralizes their knight and attacks the weak pawn on c5. }
11. Nd2 Nxc5
{ To avoid a knight exchange   11...Bxc5  After that move Black can force an endgame.  12.Qxg7  Otherwise, White loses the f2-pawn and has no compensation.  12...Bxf2+  13.Kd1  Qf6  to save a rook  14.Qxf6□  Nxf6-+  Almost all the white pawns are weaknesses. The plan for Black is to play ...Ke7, ...Ng4, ...Be3 & ...Rh5 }
12. e4 f6
{ Threatening a fork.   12...b6!  is another idea for Black to transfer the bishop to b7.  13.Be2  Bb7  The e4-pawn is hanging.  14.exd5  Bxd5∓  activating the bishop. The plan for Black is to play: ...Be7, ...Rc8, ...g5 & ...Bf6. }
13. Bg3
{ 13.Be3  a4  a positional move that restricts White's options  14.Rd1  a3⩱  After ...e5, ...Be6, ...Ra4 Black gets a very nice position. }
13... e5 14. Qxd5 Qe7
{ Black doesn't need to exchange the queens, because they will develop their pieces with tempo and obtain the advantage in development. }
15. Nb3 Nxb3 16. axb3
{ 16.Qxb3?  Be6-+  While the bishop on g3 is out of the game, Black may take advantage of their bishop activity.  17.Qb2  Qa3  18.Rb1  The pawn on c3 is a weakness anyway, regardless of what White plays.   18.Qxa3  Bxa3  19...Bb2 is also a threat.  19.Be2  Rc8-+  After ...Rxc3, ...Ke7, ...Rhc8 Black gets a completely winning position.  18...Rc8  19.Kd2  There is nothing else to suggest for White if they want to save the pawn on c3.  19...Rd8+  20.Ke1  Kf7-+  Black doesn't need to castle. Their king is well protected behind the pawns. After ...Rc8, ...Be7, ...Rhd8 Black gets a winning position. }
16... Be6
{ When we develop our pieces with a tempo that means that we control the initiative and we must attack because it is possible to lose the initiative. }
17. Qd1 Qc5 18. Qc2 { White has to protect the pawn on c3. } 18... Rc8 19. Rc1
Qc7
{ 19...f5  with the idea of ...f4 to restrict the bishop.  20.exf5   20.h3  f4  21.Bh2  The bishop on h2 is locked out and Black is a piece up, in fact. One of the World Champions - Capablanca had some significant games where he isolated an enemy piece and started to play on the other side of the board. This is the best strategy in such cases.  21...Qa3-+  Threatening to capture both pawns.  gxf5  Black has a winning position because they control the center and White has a weak bishop on g3 and weak pawns on the queenside. }
20. Bd3 Ba3 { A simple tactic where Black receives a winning endgame. } 21. Ra1
Qxc3+ 22. Qxc3 Rxc3 23. Rxa3 Rc1+ { A skewer. } 24. Kd2 Rxh1
{ Black won an exchange and showed very good technique realizing their strong position. }
25. Rxa5 O-O 26. Bc4 Rd8+ 27. Kc2 Bxc4
{ When we have a material advantage we have to exchange pieces. } 28. bxc4 Rd4
29. Ra4 Rxe4 30. f3 Re2+ 31. Kd3 Rxg2 32. Ra8+ Kf7 33. Ra7 Rd1+ 34. Kc3 Rd7 35.
c5 Ke6 36. c6 bxc6 37. b6 Rxa7
{ White resigned. After  38.bxa7  just  38...Ra2  to stop the pawn and with so many extra pawns Black is completely winning. White tried to gain the pawn after capturing on c5. Usually, such a move in London System reveals one of the most common plans, but at the same time gives up control over the center. In this game, White decided to hold the pawn on c5, which actually wasn't the best strategy. As a result, Black gained the pawn back and obtained the initiative. }
