1. d4
{ This Model Game refers toChapter 6 when White plays Qc1 to protect the b2-pawn. However, the move order in the opening here was different. But finally after 8. Qc1, the game transposed to a well-known position that you learned from the course. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Be2 e6 7. Ngf3 Qb6 8. Qc1
Be7
{ We can see this type of position in many lines of the London system but it is very interesting to see Sargissian's approach and his ideas. }
9. a4
{ It's a typical idea that White may use to chase Black's queen. There are several options for Black, but they shouldn't waste a tempo. }
9... c4
{ Other possible moves for Black are 9...a5 and 9...cxd4.   9...O-O ?  for example, castling is too slow  10.a5  Nxa5  Or the black queen has to leave it's position...  11.dxc5⩲  And Black experiences serious problems. They can't capture the c5-pawn anymore.   9...a5!?  A possible move to maintain the pressure.   9...cxd4  10.exd4  Rc8∞ }
10. O-O O-O 11. Nh4
{ A typical idea for White to chase our light-squared bishop. } 11... Be4
{ Whenever White plays Nh4, the best move for Black is ...Be4. Black either gets their knight to the center or provokes f3. }
12. Nxe4
{ Not a very popular move for White but it is still possible.   12.f3?  Bd3!  not 12...Bg6 and with the idea to make the enemy knight on the edge the object of attack.  13.Bxd3  cxd3  The knight on h4 is trapped. What should White do?  14.g3   14.g4  Nxg4∓  gaining a pawn.  14...Nd7  threatening a fork  15.Ng2  g5  The knight escaped, but now the bishop is trapped.  16.Be5  f6-+ }
12... Nxe4
{ Black centralized their knight and found one very aggressive idea which is typical for these pawn structures. }
13. Nf3 g5 { Attack on the kingside. } 14. Bg3 h5
{ With the idea of ...h4 and to take the bishop on g3. } 15. Ne5
{ 15.h4  to escape with the bishop.  15...Nxg3  16.fxg3  g4  Black grabs some space and creates several weaknesses in White's camp on the kingside.  17.Ng5  actually the knight on g5 doesn't have any squares on which to escape.  17...Na5  18.Qc2  f5∓  intending to take on g5 and then win that pawn. }
15... Nxg3
{ Black is still better in this line, but 15... h4 could lead to a much better position.   15...h4!  leads to some forced tactics which favor Black.  16.Nd7   16.Nxc6  bxc6  17.Be5  the only square to escape with the bishop.  17...f6  18.f3  The only way to not lose a minor piece.  18...Nd6  19.Bxd6  Bxd6∓  A better position with the clear plan to continue the attack on the kingside, which is one of the best plans when playing a middlegame with opposite-colored bishops.  16...Qd8  17.Nxf8  but the bishop is still hanging, while the knight is trapped.  17...hxg3∓  18.Nxe6  to exchange the knight at least for a pawn!  18...Qc8!  Black intends to capture on e6 with their queen to bring the queen to the attack.  19.fxg3   19.Nc5  trying to escape.  19...gxf2+  20.Kh1  Bxc5  the knight on e4 is more important - it supports the kingside attack.  21.dxc5  Kg7!  Threatening mate.  22.g4  Qh8-+  Black doubles on the h-file and delivers a checkmate with ...Qh3 or ...Qh2.  19...Qxe6  with a very strong position for Black. They have more space and better position of their pieces. The plan for Black is to play: ...g4, ...Nf6, ...Rd8, ...Qg6, ...f5. }
16. hxg3 Nxe5 { The white pawn structure is ruined. } 17. dxe5 g4
{ Black has to restrict the opponent's bishop with their pawns and to try to open some diagonals for their dark-squared bishop and then attack the e5 pawn. }
18. e4 Kg7
{ Black missed their chance to take advantage of that position.   18...d4!  19.Bxc4   19.Qh6  d3  The bishop is restricted.  20.Qxh5  dxe2  21.Qxg4+  Unfortunately for White, there is no perpetual check.  21...Kh7  22.Qh5+  Kg7  Finally, the bishop blocks on g5.  23.Qg4+  Kh6  24.Qh3+  24.Qf4 Bg5  24...Kg6  25.Qg4+  Bg5-+  And Black has an extra piece.  19...Rac8  an intermediate move to pressure the c-file.  20.b3  Kg7⩱  White wants to play Qh6 and to take our h5 pawn.  21.cxd4  Qxd4  Both pawns are hanging.  22.Rd1   22.Qf4  Kg6  threatening ...Bg5 trapping the queen.  23.Rfd1?  is a blunder.  23...Qxa1!  24.Rxa1  Bg5-+  Black gets extra material and an  absolutely winning position.  22...Qxe5⩱  After ...a6 Black restricts the enemy bishop and has to locate their pieces on dark squares to prevent any tactics from White. }
19. a5 Qc5 20. exd5 exd5 21. Qf4 { White has to activate their queen. } 21...
Qc6 22. b3
{ A temporary sacrifice of a pawn with the idea to open the position of the bishop. }
22... cxb3 23. Rab1 Bc5 { One of the best squares for the bishop. } 24. Rxb3 b6
25. Bd3 { Prevents Black from playing ...Qg6. } 25... Qh6
{ Exchanging the queens gives more chances for Black because the white pawns are on black squares and it is very easy to come under attack. }
26. Qf5 Qg6 { And White has to exchange queens. } 27. Rd1 Qxf5 28. Bxf5 Rfe8
29. Rxd5 Rad8 30. Rxd8 Rxd8
{ In the endgame is very important for all pieces to be active, including the king, and also to have a connection with each other. }
31. axb6 Bxb6 32. Rb2
{ A critical mistake that locks the king out of the game.   32.Kf1!  It doesn't matter that White can lose a pawn, the most important piece in the endgame is the king and White had to activate him immediately.  32...Rd2  33.Ke1⩱  White still has a chance to save the position.   32.Rb1  Rd2  attacking on f2.  33.Rf1  a5-+  Black promotes or just takes c3- and e5-pawns. }
32... Rd1+ 33. Kh2
{ White's king is isolated and Black shows very nice technique realizing the strong advantage. }
33... Rf1 34. f4
{ 34.f3  Similar to what happened in the game.  34...gxf3  35.gxf3  Rxf3⩱  . }
34... gxf3
{ 34...Rc1  provoking Rc2  35.Rc2  The white rook is no longer on the open file.  35...Re1-+  36.Rb2  Bg1+  to relocate the bishop with a tempo  37.Kh1  Bc5+  38.Kh2  White can only move their king and wait.  38...a5-+  Technically White is playing without their king and their position is lost.  39.Rb7  threatening ...e6  39...Bg1+  40.Kh1  Bf2+  Black may find a simple mating idea.  41.Kh2  Re3  42.Rb1  White stops a checkmate, but has no counterplay anymore. }
35. gxf3 Rxf3 36. g4
{ Only allows Black to create a passed pawn.   36.Bd7  Re3∓  still a winning position for Black. }
36... h4 { Black has two passed pawns and safe haven for their king. } 37. Rd2
Bc7 38. Re2 f6
{ Black takes another pawn and receives a completely winning position. } 39. c4
h3 40. Re1 Bxe5+ 41. Kh1 Kh6 42. Rc1 Kg5 43. c5 Rc3
{ 0-1 White resigns. White understood that without rooks this endgame is completely lost. I'm going to illustrate how Black wins. }
44. Rxc3 Bxc3 45. Kh2 Kh4 46. c6 Be5+ 47. Kh1 a5 48. Kg1 a4 49. Kh1 a3 50. Be6
Kg3 51. Kg1 Bd4+ 52. Kh1 Bb6
{ White is in Zugzwang and has to lose all the pawns. } 53. c7 Bxc7 54. Kg1
Bb6+ 55. Kh1 Bd4 { Still in Zugzwang. } 56. Bf7 Kxg4 *

