1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 d5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 Qb6 6. Qc2
{ Covered inchapter 7. } 6... g6 7. Nbd2 { is the mainline in this position. }
7... Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bf5
{ 9...Nh5  is themain line recommended in the course. However, I want you to understand all typical plans and ideas that Black has within this opening.  10.Be5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Nf6 }
10. dxc5
{ One of the ideas for White is to take the pawn on c5 and to give up the center. In this game, Praggnanandhaa showed a very good way to play this position. }
10... Qxc5 11. Qb3 Na5
{ 11...Rae8  Black can also sacrifice the b7-pawn for compensation:  12.Qxb7  e5  13.Nb3  Qd6=∞ }
12. Qa4 Nc6 13. Qb3 { 13...Na5 repeats the position. } 13... Nh5 14. Bg5
{ This move is not good because the bishop on g5 will be under attack.   14.Qxb7?  Nxf4  15.exf4  Rab8-+  In case of 16.Qa6 just 16...Rxb2 with equal material, but better piece activity for Black and several weaknesses in White's camp.  16.Nb3  Rxb7  17.Nxc5  Rxb2-+  Black's activity decides the game.   14.Bc7  Nb4!  a discovered attack  15.g4!  This line requires a lot of calculations.  15...Nc2!  16.gxh5  Nxa1  17.Qxb7  Rfc8=  The knight is stuck, but Black has extra exchange. }
14... h6 15. Bh4
{ Transposes toChapter 7 - @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2ppbp/1qn3p1/2pp3n/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PPQNBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bh4  Bf5  12.dxc5  Qxc5  . }
15... e5
{ Black's position looks very solid because they control the center and have more space. }
16. Rfd1 { The bishop on h4 is locked out of the game. } 16... a6
{ A useful move for Black preparing ...b5 and controlling the b5 square.   16...g5!  One of the possible ideas after ...h6.  17.Bg3  Nxg3  18.hxg3  Rfd8∓  with a very nice position for Black. They have a bishop pair, more space and a very strong center. Their plan is to play: ...Rab8, ...b5, ...e4 or ...d4. }
17. Nf1
{ 17.Ne1  Attacking the knight on h5.  17...Nf6  18.Nd3  Qe7⩱  The plan for Black is to play: ...Rac8, ...g5, ...b5 & ...a5.   17.Qxb7?  g5  18.Bg3  Nxg3  19.hxg3  Rfb8  traps the queen.  20.Nb3   20.Qc7  Ra7  20...Qd6-+ }
17... Be6 18. Qc2 Rac8 { Black brings all their pieces into the game. } 19.
Rac1
{ Also in this position, there are two strong candidate moves - ...f5 and ...g5, but probably Black wanted to improve a little bit on the queenside first. }
19... b5 20. Ng3 Nf6
{ And now Black has a simple threat to take the bishop on h4. } 21. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ Black has a pair of bishops and the next step plans to open the position. }
22. h3 Bg7
{ With the idea, ...f5   22...e4!  That move looks a bit more aggressive and restricts the opponent's pieces.  23.Ne1   23.Nd4  Nxd4  24.exd4  Qd6-+  and Black may play on both flanks.  Be5-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...f5, ...f4, ...g5, ...a4. }
23. Qb1 Rfd8
{ Black wants to improve the position of their pieces before pushing the f5 pawn. }
24. a3 Qe7 25. Bf1 f5
{ 25...Na5!?  Another interesting idea for Black to control the c4 and b3 squares with their knight.  26.b4  Nc4-+  27.Bxc4  bxc4  with a winning position for Black. Their plan is to play: ...h5, ...h4, ...Bf5 and to push one of the central pawns.   25...h5!?  A typical move for Black when the knights are on g3 and f3. }
26. Re1 Qf7
{ Black doesn't rush to push one of the central pawns because there is no counterplay for White. }
27. Rcd1 Re8 28. Qc2 d4
{ All Black's pieces are optimized, so it is time to push one of the central pawns. }
29. Nd2
{ 29.exd4  The best move White could find.  29...e4!  30.Nd2  Nxd4-+  However, even here Black is winning. }
29... dxc3
{ 29...dxe3!  This move is better because White will have a weak pawn on e3 and a bad bishop on f1.  30.fxe3  e4-+  And white knight's coordination is broken. }
30. bxc3 e4 { All the white pieces are passive and isolated. } 31. Ne2 g5
{ With the idea of ...f4. } 32. Qb2 Bd5 33. Nd4 f4
{ In the next nine moves, Black showed very nice technique for attacking the king. }
34. Nxc6 Rxc6 35. Rc1 Rec8 36. Nb1 f3
{ If we want to give checkmate, we have to destroy the protection of the king. }
37. g3 Be5 38. Red1 Rc5 39. Qb4 h5 40. a4 h4 41. g4 Bb8
{ Nothing can stop Black from entering White's kingside. } 42. Qxb5
{ White resigns. } *

