1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. e3 Qb6 6. Qb3
{ These setups are covered inchapter 8. } 6... c4 7. Qxb6
{ 7.Qc2  is more common.  7...Bf5  8.Qc1  e6  Please, followthis variation to repeat the line. }
7... axb6
{ We can see this typical pawn structure in many lines of the London system, so we must know how to attack the opponent and what defensive moves to expect from White. }
8. Na3 Bf5 9. Nb5 Ra5
{ The plan for Black is very easy: to attack the weak pawns on the queenside. Dmitrij Kollars played this game perfectly and showed a very nice plan for how to attack the opponent's weaknesses. }
10. a4 e6 11. Be2 Be7
{ The b2 and a4 pawns are objects of attack.   11...Bc2  12.Bd1  This is how White saves the pawn on a4.  12...Bxd1  13.Kxd1  Ne4  activating the knight.  14.Ke2⩱  However, Black is still better and may continue their plan. }
12. Bc7 Ra6 { Black has to protect the b6 pawn. } 13. O-O
{ 13.Bd1  O-O⩱  14.Ne5  h5  Securing the bishop on h7 and protecting from g4.  15.O-O  Rfa8∓  The plan for Black is to play ...Ne8 & ...b5. }
13... Kd7
{ In the endgame, the most important piece is the king. Castling is not necessary. }
14. Ne5+ Nxe5 15. Bxe5
{ The plan for Black is to focus all pieces on attacking the opponent's weaknesses - the pawn on a4. }
15... Bc2 16. Bd1 { White wants to eliminate one of Black's attacking pieces. }
16... Bxd1
{ 16...Bd3-+  This move is a little bit better than Bxd1 because White's bishop on d1 is passive and has to stay there to protect the pawn on a4 and there is no connection between white rooks.  17.Re1  Ra5  It is not possible to play ...Rha8 because of Nc7.  18.f3  Rha8  Step by step, Black sticks to their plan.  19.Rc1  Ne8∓  The idea of this move is to control the c7 square with their knight and to play for ...f6, ...g5, ...Nd6 and to exchange enemy active pieces.  20.Bg3   20.e4  is typical counterplay, but in this position is a blunder.  20...dxe4  21.fxe4  Bg5-+  One of white rooks is trapped.  20...h5  gaining space on the kingside and restricting enemy pieces.  21.h4  g5∓ }
17. Rfxd1 Rc8 { With the idea ...Nc7 & ...Rca8. } 18. Ra2 Ne8
{ Black controls the c7-square with their knight and prepares to push the f6-pawn. }
19. Rda1 { White is obliged to defend the weak pawn on a4 with their rooks. }
19... f6
{ With every move, Black improves their position and they follow the most important and general rule in the endgame - 'Do not rush!' }
20. Bg3 Bd6 21. Kf1 { 21.Bxd6  Nxd6  22.Nxd6  Kxd6 } 21... Rca8 22. Ke2
{ 22.Bxd6!?  Nxd6  Black has a simple threat - to take the knight on b5. And there are two defending moves for White - Nd6 and Ra3.  23.Ra3   23.Nxd6  Kxd6  24.Ra3   24.b3?  cxb3  25.Ra3  Kc6-+  After ...b5, ...Rxa4 & ...Ra1 Black has a winning position.  24...Kc6  25.Ke2  White also centralizes the most important piece in the endgame.  25...b5  26.a5   26.axb5+  Kxb5  27.Rxa6??   27.Kd2  Rxa3!  28.bxa3  It is not possible to take with the rook because White gets a losing pawn endgame.  28...g5∓  The plan for Black is to play: ...h5, ...f5, ...Kc6, ...b5, ...Kb6 & ...Ka5.  27...Rxa6-+  28.Rxa6   28.Rb1  Ka4  29.b3+  cxb3-+  Black receives a winning rook endgame.  28...bxa6  Black receives an easy winning pawn endgame but it is interesting to see how it happens.  29.Kd2  Ka4  30.Kc2  h5  31.h3  g5  32.g4  hxg4  33.hxg4  f5  34.f3  fxg4  35.fxg4  a5  36.Kb1  Kb3  37.Kc1  a4  38.Kb1  a3  39.bxa3  Kxa3-+  Then Black shoulders the white king and captures the c3-pawn.  26...g5!  Black has to push the pawns on the kingside and try to create another weakness. One important rule when we play endgame is to create two weaknesses if we want to win the game. Also when we have a space advantage we can play very easily on both flanks.  27.Kd2  h5  28.h3  e5!  29.g3  Kd6∓  The plan for Black is to play: ...Ke6, ...Kf5, ...g4, ...Ke4, ...exd4 and to attack the enemy pawns on the kingside.  23...Ne4!  24.Ke2  f5!  White can't move their rooks and the knight on b5, basically Black can play on the kingside being a piece up - their knight. When they push pawns, it is possible to create a weakness on the kingside.  25.f3  Nf6⩱  26.R3a2  g5  27.Kd2  h5⩱  The plan for Black is to play: ...h4, ...f4, ...g4, ...Rg8 and to start an attack on the kingside. }
22... Bxg3 23. hxg3 Nd6
{ 23...f5!  24.f3  Nf6∓  Black can play also in the kingside as we mentioned in the previous line. }
24. Nxd6 Kxd6 25. g4 { 25.Ra3  h5⩱  with the idea, ...f5, ...g6, ...e5. } 25...
b5 26. Kf3 { 26.a5  b6  When the pawn is lost. } 26... Rxa4 27. Rxa4 Rxa4 28.
Rb1
{ White's rook looks very passive.   28.Rxa4?  bxa4  The pawn endgame is losing for White. Black has one very famous idea which you can learn from almost any book devoted to endgames - ...b5, ...b4, ...a3, or ...c3. }
28... Kc6 29. e4 Ra2 { After this, Black won very smoothly. } 30. exd5+ Kxd5
31. Kf4 h6 32. g3 Ra4 33. Ke3 b4 34. f3 b3 35. Kd2 Ra2 36. Ke3 b5 37. Kd2 b4
38. cxb4 { 38.Ke3  Rxb2  39.Rxb2  bxc3 } 38... Kxd4 39. f4 c3+
{ White resigns. } *

