1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This setup is covered inchapter 9. } 5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The best move for Black. } 7. Rb1 Qc3 8. Bb5 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Nb3
{ The other main moves in this position are Ne5, Be5, e4 & Nd4. You can check themhere }
10... O-O 11. Qd3 Ne4 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Ne5
{ White centralizes their knight and attacks the weak pawn on c6. } 13... Bf6
{ 13...a5!  This is the only option that offers a better position for Black in this variation. A typical move for Black with idea to activate their bishop on c8.  14.Nxc6  14...Bf6  15.Qxc3  Nxc3  That line leads to an endgame which favors Black.  16.Bd6  16...Ba6  17.Bxf8  Bxf1  18.Rxf1  Kxf8⩱  19.Nbxa5  Ra6!  White can't move any of their knights. They are stuck.  20.g3  Ke8  The plan for Black is to play: ...Be7 & ...Rxa5. After that, Black is able to capture all White's weaknesses on the queenside. }
14. Nxc6
{ 14.f3!?  14...Bxe5!  15.fxe4  f6=  A very strong defending move for the Black which saves their position.  16.Nd4  Qxd3  17.cxd3  Bxd4  18.exd4  Rf7=  with an approximately equal endgame with a drawing tendency. The plan for Black is to play: ...Ba6, ...h5, ...g5, ...Kh7 & ...Rg8. }
14... Bd7 { 14...a5!  Transposes to the previous line - 13...a5. } 15. Nca5
{ 15.f3!?  Another interesting idea for White which leads to forced endgame.  15...Qxd3  16.cxd3  Nc3=  17.Ne5!  Bxe5  18.Bxe5  Nxb1  19.Rxb1  Rfc8=  Black won an exchange but White has a passed pawn well connected with the other pawns. The idea for Black is to play: ...f6, ...Rc6, ...Ra6 and try to activate their pieces. }
15... Rfc8 { The idea is to take the c5 pawn. } 16. Nb7 { Protects the pawn. }
16... e5 { Black controls the center and rendered the bishop inactive. } 17.
Bg3
{ And now we came to the position where Black has the advantage, but unfortunately makes a critical mistake and loses the game. However, until this moment Black played really well and would play for a win. }
17... Rc7
{ 17...Qb4∓  18.Nd6   18.N3a5  Qa4∓  And then Black takes the pawn on c5.  18...Nxd6  19.cxd6  Qxd6∓  With a very solid position for Black. They have the bishops, control over the center, and the rooks are ready to attack the weak pawns on c2 and a2. }
18. Nd6 { Amazing move that destroys Black's position. } 18... Qxd3 19. cxd3
Nxc5 20. Rfc1
{ White has to activate the last inactive piece into the attack. } 20... Ne6
21. Rxc7 Nxc7 22. Na5
{ 22.Nc5!  Be6⩲  With a better position for White because their pieces are more active. }
22... Na6
{ Finally, Black equalized. Although Black has pair of bishops in the endgame, White has pair of knights which are very dangerous and can create many troubles. }
23. Nab7 Rb8 24. Rb3 Bc6 25. h3 h5 26. h4 Kf8
{ 26...Bxb7!?  27.Nxb7  Rc8=  If Black gives up their pair of bishops, the position will be equal. }
27. Kh2 Kg8
{ Black doesn't have any useful moves, that's why they play a few moves with their king. }
28. f3 Kh7 29. Na5 Ba4
{ Last mistake by Black that cost them the game.   29...Rxb3⩱  30.Nxb3  Exchanging the rooks gives a little bit more chances for Black to win the game.  30...Nb4!  31.d4  exd4  32.Nxd4  Bd7⩱  The position is very complicated and the player with a better endgame technique should win the game. }
30. Ra3 Be8
{ 30...Rb4  31.Nxf7±  After e4 Black will have too many weak pieces under attack. }
31. Nxe8 Rxe8 32. Nc6 { Double attack. } 32... Nc5 33. Nxe5 Rxe5 34. d4 Re6 35.
dxc5 { White has two passed pawns and a completely winning position. } 35... a6
36. Rd3
{ In the last moves, White showed very nice technique with realizing their advantage. }
36... Kg6 37. Bf2 Re5 38. Kh3 { In the endgame, the king must be activated. }
38... Be7 39. c6 Bd6 40. Bg3 Re6 41. c7
{ The conclusion of the game is that this line in the London system leads to a lot of complicated positions both players have to know very well and also have good calculation skills. }
*

