[Black "Ellisalt Cardenas, H. vs. Estrada Nieto, J. - 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Here is a Model Game toChapter 10, when White develops the bishops first, but keeps the knights on their original positions in order to save tempi. Such a move order is quite rare among grandmasters but sometimes is used among club players. This game played by a friend of mine - Julian Estrada Nieto @@StartBracket@@who actually is an International Master with 2 GM norms@@EndBracket@@ illustrates the benefits Black gets in case White doesn't develop the knights. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3 Qb6 6. Qb3 c4
{ This time White has to exchange queens and lose a tempo with a bishop move. }
7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Bc2 b5
{ Black gets a better version of this famous endgame, where their plan is to attack on the queenside with both b-pawns. This is where ourtheory coverage ends. }
9. Nd2 b4 10. Ne2
{ While there is a bishop on c2, instead of applying a common plan with ...Bf5, Black plays a tactical strike. }
10... b3 { We stick to our plan. } 11. Bb1
{ Black has a strong advantage - they have an easy plan to attack the queenside. The opponent's pieces don't look so good but it is very important to see the ideas and maneuvers for how to win the game. }
11... e6
{ Black has a very strong pawn chain and now it's time to develop the pieces on the kingside. If you want to attack you have to use all your pieces. }
12. O-O
{ Castling is not necessary in the endgame.   12.f3!?  White should try to create counterplay on the kingside.  12...b5  13.Kf2  b4!  Pushing the b-pawns is the first step in the plan. Even if there was a white pawn on a3, ...b4 would be still possible.  14.g4  bxc3  15.Nxc3  If 15.bxc3 b2 White loses the rook.  15...Bb4-+  with idea ...Bxc3 & ...b2  16.a3  Bxc3  17.bxc3  now 17...b2 doesn't make sense.  17...Nd7-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Nb6 & ...Na4 to attack the white weaknesses. }
12... Be7 13. e4 O-O
{ The plan for Black is to play: ...b5, ...Re8, ...h6, ...b4 & ...Bb7. } 14. f3
{ 14.a3  Another way for White is to block the pawns on the queenside but that idea doesn't change Black's plan.  14...b5!  15.h3  h6  One of the typical moves for Black on the kingside.  16.Be3  Re8  17.g4  b4  with the idea of ...bxa3  18.cxb4  Nxb4-+  White can't take the knight on b4 because the rook on a1 is hanging. Also, another option for Black is to take on b4 with the bishop.  19.Rc1  Bb7  There are two options for Black: to put the bishop on b7 or d7. On b7 the bishop is more powerful.  20.e5  Nd7  21.f4  White can't create an attack on the kingside because their pieces are focused on defending the queenside.  21...Nb6  22.Kf2   22.axb4  Rxa1  23.Bh7+  Kxh7  24.Rxa1  Bxb4  and Black wins a pawn.  22...Nc6  23.Nc3  Na4  Attacking the pawn on b2.  24.Nxa4□  Rxa4-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Na7, ...Nb5, ...Ba6 & ...Rc8   14.h3  b5  Black sticks to the plan.  15.Rd1  b4!  16.cxb4  Bxb4  Threatening 17...c3  17.a3  Ba5-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Nd7, ...Nb6, ...Na4, ...h6 & ...Re8. }
14... b5 15. g4
{ 15.a3  In this line the plan for Black doesn't change: ...Re8, ...h6, ...b4 & ...Bb7.  15...Re8  16.Re1  h6  17.Be3  b4  18.cxb4  Nxb4  19.Rc1  Bb7-+  20.exd5  exd5  21.axb4  This interesting tactic doesn't change the evaluation of the position.  21...Rxa1  22.Bh7+  Kxh7  23.Rxa1  Bxb4-+  Black is a pawn up and after ...Ra8, ...c3, ...Ba6, Black gets an easily winning position. }
15... Bb7 16. Be3
{ 16.Kf2  One of the best squares for the white king.  16...b4  17.cxb4  Nxb4-+  provoking a3.  18.a3  dxe4  This move is also one of the main ideas for Black in that endgame.  19.Nxe4  Nxe4+  20.Bxe4  Nd3+  and White has to exchange their light-squared bishop.  21.Bxd3  cxd3-+  The plan for black is to play: ...Rac8, ...Rc2, ...g5 & ...f5. }
16... h6 17. h4
{ 17.e5!?  This move doesn't change the plan for Black.  17...Nd7  18.f4  b4  19.Nf3  bxc3  20.Nxc3  Bb4  21.Bd2  f6!  A typical move against such a kind of a pawn structure on the kingside.  22.exf6  Nxf6-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Bxc3 & ...Ne4. }
17... Nd7
{ a critical mistake that loses almost all the advantage Black had before.   17...dxe4!  18.Nxe4  Nd5-+  The knight on d5 looks very strong. The plan for Black is to play: ...Rfd8, ...g5, ...b4, ...f5 & ...e5. }
18. h5
{ 18.exd5  With this move, White could get a bit closer to an equal position.  18...bxa2  19.Rxa2  exd5  20.Rxa8  Rxa8  21.g5⩱  Black is still better, but right now they don't have a clear plan of how to enter into the enemy camp. }
18... Nb6 19. Nf4
{ 19.Kf2  Ra7  with the idea of ...Ra8 & ...bxa2.  20.g5  hxg5  21.Rg1  Rfa8-+  Threatening to take and push the other b-pawn. }
19... Bg5 20. exd5 exd5 21. Bf5
{ With the idea to exchange rook via the a-file. } 21... Rfe8
{ The rooks are more powerful on open files. } 22. Kf2 Rxa2
{ 22...Rxe3!  23.Kxe3  bxa2-+  with the idea of ...Re8. } 23. Rxa2 bxa2 24. Ra1
Ra8 { Of course, Black has to protect their passed pawn. } 25. Ne2
{ White decided to simplify the position. } 25... Bxe3+ 26. Kxe3 Ne7
{ An unnecessary move. If we want to win we have to attack, not to defend.   26...b4-+  27.cxb4  otherwise, 27...b3  27...Nxb4  28.Nc3  Bc8-+  with the idea of ...Bxf5, ...Na4 & ...Ra5. }
27. Bc2
{ This is where both players are already in time trouble, that's why you can find tons of mistakes in their play.   27.Nc1⩱  If white takes the passed pawn on a2, they will have a chance to save the position.  27...Nxf5+  28.gxf5  Kf8  In the endgame, the most important piece is the king.  29.Nf1  Nd7⩱  with the idea of ...Ke7, ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@...Nb6-Na4@@EndBracket@@. }
27... Nec8
{ 27...b4-+  28.cxb4  Nc6-+  with the idea of ...Nxb4, ...Re8, ...Bc6 & ...Ba4. }
28. Nc1 Nd6 { ...b4 is still possible in this position. } 29. Rxa2 Na4
{ 29...Kf8=  Black had to improve their position by centralizing the king. }
30. Bxa4
{ 30.Nf1⩲  with idea Kf2, Ne3 and to attack the weak pawn on d5  30...Kf8  31.Kf2  Ne8  32.Ne3  Ra6 }
30... bxa4 31. Ne2 Kf8 { Black must activate the king. } 32. Kf2 Bc6
{ Protects the pawn on a4. } 33. Nb1 Rb8 34. Na3 f5
{ As you know in the endgame one weakness is not enough to win the game, we must create another one. }
35. Nc2 fxg4 36. fxg4 Ke7 { Preparing ...Rf8. } 37. Ng3
{ 37.Nf4=  is an equal and very complicated endgame. } 37... Rf8+
{ If one piece is isolated on one of the flanks, we start an attack on the other side of the board. }
38. Kg2 Ne4
{ 38...Bd7  39.Ne3  Kf6⩱  with the idea of ...Kg5, ...Kf4, ...Ne4 & ...Rb8. }
39. Nxe4
{ 39.Nb4⩲  White missed their chance to receive a better rook endgame.  39...Kd7□  40.Nxc6  Kxc6  41.Nxe4  dxe4  42.Rxa4±  with the idea of ...Ra5, ...Re5 & ...Rc5. }
39... dxe4 40. Ne3 { Block and Attack. } 40... Rf3 41. Nf5+
{ 41.d5=  Last chance for White to save the game.  41...Bd7  42.Nxc4  Kf6= }
41... Kf6
{ Black found a very nice route for their king and receives a winning position. }
42. Ra1 e3 43. Kh2 Kg5 44. Rg1 Rf2+
{ Black successfully outplayed White in the middlegame and early endgame because of a better original position and better understanding of the features of this typical London System/Slav Defense ending. However, when both players got into time trouble, they started making mistakes and the game could have ended in a draw. }
*

