1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6
{ 6. Qb3, 6. Qc1 & 6. Qc2 are the most popular moves in this line. } 6. b3
{ The passive b3 setups are covered inchapter 11. } 6... cxd4 7. exd4 Bf5 8.
Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 10. O-O Be7 11. h3 O-O 12. Nbd2 Rac8
{ The pawn on c3 is a permanent weakness, and that's why top players avoid this variation and don't play 6. b3 }
13. a4
{ One of the main plans for White in that position is to push the pawns on the queenside. }
13... Rfd8
{ Black has to focus all their pieces on the queenside and in the center. In thecourse I recommend  13...h6  as prophylaxis against an eventual Bg5. }
14. b4 Bd6
{ One of the typical ideas for Black in this kind of position is to exchange their inactive bishop with White's active bishop on the kingside. Black is ok with 15. Bg5, they can just let White capture on f6. However, if you feel uncomfortable with double pawns on f7 & f6, you may continue with 14...Nh5 instead.   14...Nh5  15.Bh2  Bd6⩱  Including 14...Nh5 prevents White from playing Bg5. }
15. Bxd6
{ 15.Bg5  doesn't seem to be a problem at all for a qualified chess player.  15...Qc7  16.Bxf6  gxf6⩱  White can't take advantage of Black's king being exposed. Moreover, the f6-pawn attacks the e5-square which limits White's options. }
15... Rxd6
{ We have an equal position with very easy play for Black on the queenside. }
16. b5
{ 16.a5?!  a possible plan that actually doesn't offer any advantage for White  16...Qc7  17.Rfc1  Rdd8  With a clear plan to relocate pieces, play some prophylactic moves and preparing to attack c3. }
16... Na5
{ The knight on a5 blocks the a4 pawn and control the c4 and b3 squares. } 17.
Ne5 { The best place for the knights is in the center. } 17... a6
{ 17...Rdd8!?  The plan for Black is to play: ...Rc7, ...Rdc8 and to put pressure on the weak c3 pawn.  18.f4  A typical move in these kinds of pawns structures.  18...Rc7  19.f5  The only active plan for White if they want to play for a win.  19...exf5  20.Rxf5  White has a little bit more space on the kingside.  20...Rdc8  21.Rc1  Qd6  The plan for Black is to play ...a6, ...h6, ...Qe6 & ...f6. }
18. Rab1
{ 18.bxa6?!  That move is not good because Black will have one more semi-open file where the black rooks can operate.  18...Qxa6⩱  19.Qg3  Rb6  The plan for Black is to play: ...Rb2, ...h6 & ...Nc6. }
18... Ne8 { With the idea of ...f6. } 19. Rfc1 axb5 20. Rxb5 Qa7
{ White's pieces are a little bit more active but Black is defending well and it is very hard for White to take any advantage. }
21. Qb1 Rc7 22. Ndf3 f6 { It's time to remove the active knight on e5. } 23.
Nd3 Nc4 { Step by step Black improves the position of their pieces. } 24. Rb4
Rdc6 25. Nf4 Re7 { Whatever White plays, Black has a good response. } 26. Re1
b6
{ Black's knight on c4 has a very strong position - blocks White's weak pawns on the queenside and protects the weak pawn on b6. }
27. Qd1 g6 28. Nh2 Qc7 29. g3 g5
{ 29...f5!?  Black has a very strong pawns chain and after ...Nf6, ...Ne4, ...Kg7, ...h6, ...g5 their position may allow them to attack on the kingside. }
30. Nh5 Kf7 31. Kg2 Ncd6
{ White is slightly better now, but it's not enough to play for a win. } 32.
Qd3 Kf8 33. Rc1 Ne4 { Centralizing the knight. } 34. Ng4 Rf7 35. f3
{ After a few exchanges, there will be no counterplay for either side. } 35...
Rxc3 36. Rxc3 Qxc3 37. Qxc3 Nxc3 38. Rxb6 { The endgame is completely equal. }
38... Ra7 39. Rxe6 Rxa4 40. Ngxf6 Nxf6 41. Rxf6+ Ke7
{ This is where players agreed to a draw. I'm going to demonstrate a possible continuation that illustrates that this position is absolutely drawing. To sum it up, I should admit that this variation leads to very easy play for both sides with no tactics and risks. If neither side makes big mistakes, the game will be equal. }
42. Rh6 Ra2+ 43. Kf1 Ra1+
{ Black threatens a perpetual check or at least cuts the enemy king off. } 44.
Kf2 Ra2+ 45. Ke3
{ 45.Ke1  Nb5  White pawns are also weak.  46.Rxh7+  Kd6  47.f4  Nxd4  While the white king is passive, it's easy to make a draw. Black can even sacrifice the knight for white pawns, because the endgame with a rook vs rook + knight is theoretically drawing. }
45... Nd1+ 46. Kd3 Rb2
{ Nothing can stop Black from a perpetual check with their knight. } *

