{ Here is a Model Game forChapter 12, which illustrates how Black should play on the queenside in the middlegame. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Qb3
{ If you meet this move order, I kindly recommend playing  6...Qd7  which offers a better position than 6...Qc8 played in this game. However, knowledge of 6...Qc8 line is also required, because we can get this position if White plays Ngf3 before Qb3.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp1b2/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP1N1PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ngf3  e6  7.Qb3  Qc8  This is themove order recommended in the course. }
6... Qc8
{ 6...Qb6?!  7.dxc5  And Black has to take White queen and play without a pawn.   6...Qd7!?  7.Ngf3  c4   not  7...e6  because of  8.Ne5  or 8. Bb5  8.Qd1   8.Qb5  Nh5  followschapter 12  8...e6  . }
7. Ngf3 e6
{ We transpose to the main position from the move order -   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nf6  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nd2  Bf5  6.Ngf3  e6  7.Qb3  . }
8. Nh4
{ One of the main moves in this position. Another options for white are: c4, Be2, h3, Ne5. }
8... Be4
{ The best response for Black after Nh4. Whenever White targets our bishop on f5 with Nh4, we should play ...Be4 without thinking. }
9. f3
{ 9.Nxe4  Nxe4  Threatening ...g7-g5  10.Nf3  Be7  Still threatening ...g7-g5  11.h4  O-O =  And Black focuses on the queenside. }
9... Bg6 10. g4
{ We can see a similar position in one of the lines of the Slav defense.   10.Nxg6!?  hxg6  11.g4  To prevent Nh5  11...a6  12.Be2  Qd7  with idea ...c4, ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...g5, ...b5. }
10... Be7 { A logical move to develop the last minor piece into the game. } 11.
Bg3 a6
{ The idea of this move is to prevent the move Bb5 and to prepare ...b5 & ...c4.   11...Nd7!?  Black can try to play another plan which is also good for Black.  12.Be2  c4  13.Qd1  b5!?  You can analyze the game between: Reichmann,H - Kollars,D 2021, 0-1. }
12. Nxg6
{ 12.Be2  Qd7  13.Kf2  I highly recommend analyzing the games between Straka, Z - Iotov, V, 2018, 1/2 and Murray, T - Stephan, J, 2019, 1/2. }
12... hxg6 13. Bg2
{ 13.Be2!?  Qd7  14.Kf2   14.O-O !?  O-O  The plan for Black is to play: ...b5, ...cxd4, ...Bd6, ...e5, ...Na5!?  14...O-O  15.Kg2  Transposing to the game Murray, T - Stephan, J , 2019, 1/2. }
13... b5 { Black starts an attack on the queenside. } 14. O-O
{ 14.Qd1!?  This move doesn't change the plan for Black to attack on the queenside.  14...O-O  15.O-O  a5⩱  with ...Qb7 & ...b4 in the next few moves. }
14... O-O 15. h3
{ A critical position where Black should come up with a plan. However, it's obvious that Black should focus on the queenside. }
15... Nd7
{ With the idea to move the knight to b6 & c4   15...Qd7∓  This move is better because Black has to connect the rooks and focus all pieces on the queenside.  16.Rfc1  Rfc8  with the idea ...b4, ...a5 & ...Bd6. }
16. Rac1 Nb6 { 16...cxd4  17.cxd4  Nb6!  with idea ...Qd7, ...Nc4 & ...Nb4. }
17. Kh2 Qd7 { The best home for the queen is on the d7 square. } 18. Rcd1
{ 18.Qd1  cxd4  19.exd4  b4∓  We stick to our plan.  20.f4  bxc3  21.bxc3  Rac8∓  The plan for Black is to play: ...Bd6, ...Ne7 & ...Nc4. }
18... cxd4 { Black is strategically winning - White has no counterplay. } 19.
cxd4 { 19.exd4  b4!  with the idea ...a5 or ...Na5. } 19... Rfc8
{ Black concentrates everything on the queenside. } 20. Rc1
{ 20.f4!?  Nc4  21.Nf3  a5-+  with the idea of ...a4 & ...Nb4. } 20... Nc4
{ A typical move for this kind of a pawn structure. Exchanging knights on c4 favors Black, but White can't tolerate the knight on c4. }
21. Nxc4 bxc4 22. Qa4 Bd6
{ Black has to exchange White's active bishop to be able to occupy the b-file. }
23. f4
{ White avoids this exchange.   23.b3  The only way for White to extinguish Black's initiative.  23...cxb3  24.axb3  Bxg3+  25.Kxg3  Our knight looks stronger than the opponent's bishop and practically, White doesn't have as much play as Black because if they try to start an attack on the kingside their king will be exposed.  25...Qd6+  26.f4  g5-+  with idea ...Ne7 & ...Ng6. With this move, Black tries to tie enemy pieces down to the protection of the f4-pawn and then enter into the enemy camp via the c-file. }
23... Qb7
{ 23...Rab8!  It is better to put the rook on the semi-open file rather than the queen.  24.Rb1  Rb5-+  The pawn on a6 is poisoned. }
24. Rf2
{ 24.e4  If White tries to push the pawns on the kingside, it won't be dangerous for Black.  24...Nb4  25.e5  Be7  26.f5  Qa7-+  White has more weaknesses. The plan for Black is to play: ...Nd3, ...Rab8 & ...Rf8. }
24... Nb4 25. Bf1 Qb5
{ White is obliged to exchange the queens and the endgame will be losing for them. }
26. Qxb5 axb5 27. a3
{ 27...Nd3  no longer works, but Black may relocate their knight. } 27... Nc6
{ The plan for black remains the same: attack on the queenside. } 28. f5 Bxg3+
29. Kxg3 gxf5
{ 29...exf5-+  30.gxf5  Re8  Another weak pawn appears on the horizon.  31.Rc3  gxf5  32.Rxf5  Black also has a weakness on d5.  32...Ne7  33.Rf4  g6-+  The plan for Black is to play: ...Kg7, ...Nf5, ...Ra6 & ...Nh5. }
30. gxf5 Re8 { Black wanted to locate their rook on e8 in advance. } 31. Bg2 b4
{ 31...Rad8∓  Black has to protect the weak pawn on d5.  32.fxe6  Rxe6  33.Rc3  Ne7  with idea ...Rg6, ...Ra6, ...g6 & ...Kg7. }
32. fxe6 fxe6 33. axb4
{ White missed their chance to take advantage of the position.   33.Rxc4⩲  bxa3  34.bxa3  Ne7  35.Rc3⩲  White has a passed pawn and more chances to win the game. }
33... Nxb4 34. Bf1
{ 34.Rcf1  Nd3  35.Rd2  Rf8  The game looks equal but both sides should play very carefully. }
34... e5
{ 34...Rf8!  35.Rxf8+  Kxf8⩱  The plan for Black is to play: ...Ke7, ...Kd6, ...Ra2 }
35. Rf5
{ 35.e4!  An amazing move that equalize the position.  35...exd4  36.exd5  Re3+  37.Rf3  Rxf3+  38.Kxf3  Rf8+  39.Ke4  d3  40.d6 }
35... exd4 36. exd4 Rab8
{ 36...Re3+!  A great chance for Black to activate their two rooks with a tempo.  37.Kg4   37.Rf3  Rxf3+  38.Kxf3  Kf7  with the idea ...Kf6, ...Ra2 & ...Nc2.   37.Kf2  Rb3  37...Re4+  38.Rf4  Trying to save the pawn on d4.  38...Rxf4+  39.Kxf4  Kf7⩱  This position is better for Black because their minor pieces look are more active than the White's. Both the d- & and the b-pawn are weak. }
37. Bg2 Red8 38. Ra1
{ A very nice idea for White to activate their passive rook on the open file and to put it on the 7th rank. }
38... Rb5 39. Ra7 Nc6 40. Rc7 Nxd4 41. Rff7
{ This is a dream position for the rooks. } 41... Ne6 42. Ra7
{ A critical mistake.   42.Rcd7  42...d4  43.Rxg7+!  Because of this move, White draws the game...  43...Nxg7  44.Rxd8+  Kf7  45.Rd7+  Kf6  46.Bd5  White can simply sacrifice the bishop for a pawn, because Rook+Knight vs. Rook is a theoretically drawing position. }
42... d4 43. h4 d3
{ 43...Rb3+-+  Here is the last chance for Black to win the game with a typical sacrifice.  44.Kg4   44.Rf3  d3  45.Bh3  Nc5  46.Rff7  d2+  47.Kg2  Nb7  Interfering on the 7th rank.  44...Rxb2  45.Kg3  Rxg2+!  46.Kxg2  c3-+  While Black successfully secures the weakness on g7, they can just push the pawns forward and promote them. }
44. Bh3 { White attacks the defender of the g7 pawn and equalizes the game. }
44... Re5 45. Bxe6 Re3+ 46. Kg2 Rxe6 47. Rxg7+ Kf8 48. Raf7+ { Repetition. }
48... Ke8 49. Rc7 Kf8 50. Rcf7+ Ke8 51. Rc7 Kf8 52. Rcf7+
{ In this game Black outplayed White in the opening and obtained a much better position with a clear plan to play on the queenside. They were playing almost without mistakes in the middlegame, but after transitioning into an almost winning endgame, allowed White to equalize several times. As for the endgame technique, it requires improvement for both players. }
